 (writer)|Tom Taylor]]\n* [[Darek Thompson]]\n* [[Dan Thorsland]]\n* [[Erik Tiemens]]\n* [[Timothy Truman]]\n* [[Tom Veitch]]\n* [[John Wagner]]\n* [[Chris Warner]]\n* [[Nathan Walker]]\n* [[Andi Watson]]\n* [[Rob Williams (comics)|Rob Williams]]\n* [[Ryder Windham]]\n* [[Judd Winick]]\n* [[Jim Woodring]]\n* [[Timothy Zahn]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Star Wars manga==\n{{Main|Star Wars manga}}\nAll are direct adaptations of the films or canonical from canonical novels.\n===Film adaptations into manga===\nProduced before Disney.\n\n* ''[[Star Wars (manga)|Episode I: The Phantom Menace]]'' (manga) by [[Kia Asamiya]]\n* ''[[Star Wars (manga)|Episode IV: A New Hope]]'' (manga) by [[Hisao Tamaki]]\n* ''[[Star Wars (manga)|Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (manga) by [[Toshiki Kudo]]\n* ''[[Star Wars (manga)|Episode VI: Return of the Jedi]]'' (manga) by Shin-ichi Hiromoto\n\n====''Star Wars: Story Before the Force Awakens'' (2015)====\n\nThe comics listed here are licensed by Disney, but were not released by Marvel or Disney-Lucasfilm Press. Their canonical status is disputed due to some minor changes made to the story due to cultural interpretation but all are film adaptations.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=jenheddle |number=604430151309365249 |date=May 29, 2015 |title=@DarthSpiriah @pauldunahoo @MasterAndrew15 It is approved but its canon status is grey area. We gave them leeway for cultural interpretation |accessdate=2016-12-19}}</ref> \n\n''Star Wars: Story Before the Force Awakens'' is a [[webcomic]] adaptation of the original trilogy by Korean artist and writer Hong Jac-ga. The strips were translated to English and have been made available worldwide on [[Line Webtoon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webtoons.com/en/sf/Star%20Wars/list?title_no=544|title=Star Wars, List1 {{!}} LINE Webtoon}}</ref> ''The Story Before the Force Awakens'' spans the \"Rise of the Empire Era\" and the \"Rebellion Era\". \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* ''An Old Friend'' (Issue #1) (12 BBY\u20136 BBY)\n* ''Meeting the Droids'' (Issue #2) (6 BBY\u20130 BBY)\n* ''Beginning of an Adventure'' (Issue #3) (0 BBY)\n* ''Only Hope'' (Issue #4) (0 BBY)\n* ''Escape'' (Issue #5) (0 BBY)\n* ''Death Star'' (Issue #6) (0 BBY)\n* ''Rescue'' (Issue #7) (0 BBY)\n* ''Darth Vader'' (Issue #8) (0 BBY)\n* ''Vanishing into the Force'' (Issue #9) (0 BBY)\n* ''The Little Spark'' (Issue #10) (0 BBY)\n* ''X-Wing'' (Issue #11) (0 BBY)\n* ''One Shot'' (Issue #12) (0 BBY)\n* ''Awakening of the Force'' (Issue #13) (0 BBY)\n* ''Miracle of Yavin'' (Issue #14) (0 BBY)\n{{col-3}}\n* ''Suffering'' (Issue #15) (3 ABY)\n* ''Strike'' (Issue #16) (3 ABY)\n* ''Retreat'' (Issue #17) (3 ABY)\n* ''Dagobah'' (Issue #18) (3 ABY)\n* ''Master Yoda'' (Issue #19) (3 ABY)\n* ''Training'' (Issue #20) (3 ABY)\n* ''Dark Side of Force'' (Issue #21) (3 ABY)\n* ''Calling'' (Issue #22) (3 ABY)\n* ''Trap'' (Issue #23) (3 ABY)\n* ''Unprepared Duel'' (Issue #24) (3 ABY)\n* ''The Cruel Truth'' (Issue #25) (3 ABY)\n* ''Choice'' (Issue #26) (3 ABY)\n* ''Determination'' (Issue #27) (3 ABY)\n{{col-3}}\n* ''Jabba's Palace'' (Issue #28) (4 ABY)\n* ''Pit of Carkoon'' (Issue #29) (4 ABY)\n* ''Lightsaber'' (Issue #30) (4 ABY)\n* ''Rescue'' (Issue #31) (4 ABY)\n* ''Secret of Birth'' (Issue #32) (4 ABY)\n* ''Forest Moon'' (Issue #33) (4 ABY)\n* ''Protectors of the Forest'' (Issue #34) (4 ABY)\n* ''Surrender'' (Issue #35) (4 ABY)\n* ''The Emperor'' (Issue #36) (4 ABY)\n* ''Rage'' (Issue #37) (4 ABY)\n* ''Light vs. Dark'' (Issue #38) (4 ABY)\n* ''Epiphany'' (Issue #39) (4 ABY)\n* ''The End'' (Issue #40) (4 ABY)\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Novel adaptations into manga===\n{{Main|Star Wars manga}}\nThe comics listed here are licensed by Disney, but were not released by Marvel or Disney-Lucasfilm Press. Their canonical status is disputed due to some minor changes made to the story due to cultural interpretation, but all adapt canonical novels.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=jenheddle |number=604430151309365249 |date=May 29, 2015 |title=@DarthSpiriah @pauldunahoo @MasterAndrew15 It is approved but its canon status is grey area. We gave them leeway for cultural interpretation |accessdate=2016-12-19}}</ref>\n\n====''[[Star Wars: Lost Stars]]'' (2017)====\n''Star Wars: Lost Stars'' is a webcomic adaptation of the [[Claudia Gray]] novel of the same name by Japanese artist and writer Komiyama Yuusaku. The strips debuted May 4, 2017 on the Japanese version of [[Line Webtoon]].<ref name=\"loststars\">{{cite web|title=LINE\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u3001\u300cLINE\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb \u6625\u306e\u65b0\u9023\u8f097\u9023\u5f3e\u300d\u3092\u958b\u59cb|url=https://linecorp.com/ja/pr/news/ja/2017/1720|publisher=LINE |accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref> A trade paperback will be released in December 2017, with an English translation to be released in May 2018.<ref name=\"yenpress\">{{cite web|last1=Nadine|title=Yen Press Announces a Manga Adaptation of Star Wars: Lost Stars|url=http://yenpress.com/2017/11/yen-press-announces-a-manga-adaptation-of-star-wars-lost-stars/ |publisher=Yen Press|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref> Spans the ''Rise of the Empire Era'', the ''Rebellion Era'', and the ''New Republic Era'', from approximately 11 years before ''Episode IV: A New Hope'' to 1 year after ''Episode VI: Return of the Jedi''.\n*Volume 1 (December 2017)\n**Prologue #1 (May 2017)\n**Prologue #2 (May 2017)\n**Issue #1 (June 2017)\n**Artwork #1 (June 2017)\n**Issue #2 (July 2017)\n**Issue #3 (July 2017)\n**Issue #4 (August 2017)\n**Issue #5 (August 2017)\n**Issue #6 (September 2017)\n**Issue #7 (September 2017)\n**Issue #8 (October 2017)\n**Issue #9 (October 2017)\n**Issue #10 (November 2017)\n**Issue #11 (November 2017)\n*Uncollected\n**Issue #12 (December 2017)\n**Artwork #2 (December 2017)\n**Issue #13 (January 2018)\n**Issue #14 (January 2018)\n**Issue #15 (February 2018)\n**Issue #16 (February 2018)\n**Issue #17 (March 2018)\n**Issue #18 (March 2018)\n**Issue #19 (April 2018)\n**Issue #20 (May 2018)\n**Issue #21 (May 2018)\n**Issue #22 (June 2018)\n**Issue #23 (July 2018)\n**Issue #24 (July 2018)\n**Issue #25 (August 2018)\n\n====''Star Wars: Leia, Princess of Alderaan'' (2018)====\n''Star Wars: Leia, Princess of Alderaan'' is a webcomic adaptation of the [[Claudia Gray]] novel of the same name by Japanese artist Komiyama Yusaku. The strips are set to debut in June 2018 on the Japanese version of [[Line Webtoon]].<ref name=\"princessofalderaan\">{{cite web|title=\u3010LINE\u30de\u30f3\u30ac\u3011\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30fb\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30ba\u30b9\u30d4\u30f3\u30aa\u30d5\u5c0f\u8aac\u306e\u516c\u5f0f\u30b3\u30df\u30ab\u30e9\u30a4\u30ba\u30ec\u30fc\u30d9\u30eb\u300cLINE STAR WARS COMICS\u300d\u3092\u65b0\u305f\u306b\u8a2d\u7acb|url=https://linecorp.com/ja/pr/news/ja/2017/1984 |publisher=LINE |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Set approximately three years before ''Episode IV: A New Hope''.\n\n====''Star Wars: Lords of the Sith'' and ''Star Wars: Heir to the Jedi'' (2018)====\n''Star Wars: Lords of the Sith'' and ''Star Wars: Heir to the Jedi'' are Japanese comic adaptations of the novels by the same names. The comics were published by [[Line Webtoon]] and feature art submitted by AOKI, winner of a fan contest. Both comics have debuted in 2018.\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.darkhorse.com/Zones/StarWars/Timeline Dark Horse, publisher of most ''Star Wars'' Comics: timeline]\n* [http://starwars.wikia.com/wiki/List_of_comics List of ''Star Wars'' comic books] on [[Wookieepedia]]\n* [http://www.starwarstimeline.net/Complete%20Saga.htm The Star Wars Extended Universe Timeline]\n\n{{Star Wars}}\n{{Star Wars comics}}\n\n[[Category:Comics based on Star Wars| ]]\n[[Category:Star Wars lists|Comics]]\n[[Category:Lists of comics based on works|Star Wars]]\n[[Category:Lists of stories|Star Wars comics]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Star Wars comic books}}\n\n[[es:Star Wars (historieta)]]\n[[fr:Star Wars (bande dessin\u00e9e)]]\n[[hu:Star Wars k\u00e9preg\u00e9nyek list\u00e1ja]]\n", "name_user": "Fah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eA New Hope", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_comic_books"}
{"title_page": "Jacy Reese", "text_new": "{{short description|American social scientist}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Jacy Reese\n| image              = Jacy Reese.jpg\n| caption            = Reese speaking at the [[University of Oslo]] in 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|12|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Huntsville, Texas|Huntsville]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Texas at Austin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jacyreese.com/assets/downloads/cv.pdf|title=Jacy Reese Curriculum Vitae|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| partner            = Kelly Witwicki\n| relatives          = \n| occupation         = Writer\n}}\n\n'''Jacy Reese''' ({{IPAc-en|'|d\u0292|e\u026a|s|i\u02d0|_|\u02c8|r|i\u02d0|s}})<ref name=\"Animals and The Far Future\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NTV81NZSuKw|title=Animals and the Far Future|website=Youtube|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>; born December 16, 1992) is a writer, social scientist, and co-founder of [[Sentience Institute]]. He previously worked as a Senior Fellow at [[Sentience Politics]], and before that at [[Animal Charity Evaluators]] as chair of the board of directors and then as a full-time researcher.\n\nHis research focuses on [[effective altruism]], [[Speciesism|anti-speciesism]], and [[plant-based]] and [[cellular agriculture]]. Reese was recognized as one of [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]\u2019s \u201cHumans of the Year\u201d in December 2017 along with his co-founder Kelly Witwicki.<ref name=\"Gault 1\">{{cite web|last=Gault |first=Matthew |date=28 December 2017 |title=This Think Tank Wants to End Factory Farming |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/ev5v9n/this-think-tanks-wants-to-end-factory-farming |publisher=Vice Motherboard}}</ref> His book, ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'', argues that animal farming will end by 2100.\n\n==Career==\nBefore he graduated from college, Reese was working on the [[Animal Charity Evaluators]] Board of Directors and then joined as a full-time researcher after graduation.<ref name=\"Livegan\">{{cite podcast |last1=Lahey |first1=Kevin |last2=Le Roi |first2=Ben |title=Livegan |date=12 December 2017|time=1:20|url=https://www.buzzsprout.com/128075/609587-e8-jacy-reese |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Animal Charity Evaluators (ACE, formerly called Effective Animal Activism) is an organization within the [[effective altruism]] movement that evaluates and compares various animal charities based on their cost-effectiveness and transparency, particularly those that are tackling [[factory farming]].<ref name=\"auto\">Daniel Engber, [http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2016/08/animal_activists_crunched_the_numbers_to_learn_that_the_creature_most_in.html \"Save the Chicken\"], ''Slate'', August 18, 2016.</ref> While at ACE, Reese published an article that addressed the issue of [[wild animal suffering]], arguing that humans should act on behalf of wild animals to alleviate their suffering if it can be done safely and effectively.<ref name=\"Reese 2\">{{cite web|last=Reese |first=Jacy |date=14 December 2015 |title=Wild animals endure illness, injury, and starvation. We should help. |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/14/9873012/wild-animals-suffering |publisher=Vox}}</ref> His 2015 [[Vox (website)|Vox]] article on the topic was criticized by writers who argued we shouldn't intervene or that we should instead focus on helping domestic animals.<ref name=\"Gunther\">{{cite web|last=Gunther |first=Kristen |date=15 December 2015 |title=Nature is Violent |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/qkjpwp/nature-is-violent/ |publisher=Motherboard}}</ref><ref name=\"Matthews\">{{cite web|last=Matthews |first=Susan |date=16 December 2015 |title=Nature Can't Exist Without Suffering\u2014And We Can't Change That |url=http://www.audubon.org/news/nature-cant-exist-without-suffering-and-we-cant-change |publisher=Audubon}}</ref><ref name=\"McGrath\">{{cite web|last=McGrath |first=Lauren-Elizabeth |date=16 December 2015 |title=Vox Fails to Mention 56 Billion Lives in Piece on Animal Suffering |url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2015/12/16/animal-charity-evaluators-representative-forgets-to-mention-56-billion-animals-when-discussing-animal-suffering-and-deaths/ |publisher=Ecorazzi}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year and a half at Animal Charity Evaluators, Reese briefly worked with [[Sentience Politics]], a project of the Effective Altruism Foundation. Sentience Politics then split into two organizations, one of which was Sentience Institute, co-founded by Reese and his now-fianc\u00e9e Kelly Witwicki in June 2017.<ref name=\"Livegan\" /><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 August 2018 |title=Introducing Sentience Institute |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/blog/introducing-sentience-institute |last1=Witwicki |first1=Kelly |last2=Reese |first2=Jacy|publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref> Sentience Institute is an [[effective altruism]] think tank working to understand and facilitate the expansion of humanity's \"moral circle\" to all sentient beings. They have published research reports including a study of the British [[antislavery]] movement, a study of the French [[nuclear power]] movement, a study of [[genetically modified food]], and a poll of American attitudes towards \u201canimal farming and animal-free food.\u201d<ref name=\"Gault 1\" /><ref name=\"Sentience Institute - Research\">{{cite web|accessdate=29 December 2017 |title=Research |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/research |publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref><ref name=\"Gault 2\">{{cite web|last=Gault |first=Matthew |date=16 November 2018 |title=Jacy Reese Thinks Technology and Ethics Will See the \u2018End of Animal Farming\u2019 |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/vbavgm/jacy-reese-thinks-technology-and-ethics-will-see-the-end-of-animal-farming |publisher=Vice Motherboard}}</ref> The poll was done in collaboration with [[Ipsos|Ipsos Group]] and found that 47% of Americans support \u201ca ban on slaughterhouses.\u201d<ref name=\"Chiorando\">{{cite web|last=Chiorando |first=Maria |date=20 November 2017 |title=Poll Shows 47% Of Americans 'Agree With Ban On Slaughterhouses' |url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/poll-shows-47-of-americans-agree-with-ban-on-slaughterhouses |publisher=Plant Based News}}</ref><ref name=\"Starostinetskaya 2\">{{cite web|last=Starostinetskaya |first=Anna |date=21 November 2017 |title=Nearly Half of Americans Want to Ban Slaughterhouses |url=http://vegnews.com/articles/page.do?pageId=7509&catId=1 |publisher=VegNews}}</ref><ref name=\"Neff\">{{cite web|last=Neff |first=Michelle |date=21 November 2017 |title=New Poll Reveals Nearly 50% of Americans Want to Ban Slaughterhouses and Would Prefer Animal-Free Meat |url=http://www.onegreenplanet.org/news/americans-want-to-ban-slaughterhouses/ |publisher=One Green Planet}}</ref><ref name=\"Ettinger\">{{cite web|last=Ettinger |first=Jill |date=21 November 2017 |title=70% of Americans Want Better Treatment for Farm Animals, Poll Finds |url=http://www.organicauthority.com/70-of-americans-want-better-treatment-for-farm-animals-poll-finds/ |publisher=Organic Authority}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'', Reese \"outlines an evidence-based roadmap to a humane, ethical, efficient food system where slaughterhouses are obsolete\".<ref name=\"Spector\">{{cite web|last=Spector |first=Nicole |date=1 March 2017 |title=Fowl play? Subway denies its chicken is only 50% real |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/34634185/fowl-play-subway-denies-its-chicken-is-only-50-real |publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Publisher's Marketplace\">{{cite web|title=Dealmaker: Beacon Press (Imprint)| publisher=Publishers Marketplace| accessdate=29 December 2017 |url=https://www.publishersmarketplace.com/dealmakers/detail.cgi?id=2264}}</ref> Reese wrote this book from the perspective of [[effective altruism]] because there is already much content explaining the problems of animal agriculture, but he perceived a need for a book to guide the \"farmed animal movement\" towards its long-term goal.<ref name=\"Piper\">{{cite web|last=Piper |first=Kelsey |date=15 November 2018 |title=We could end factory farming this century |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/15/18088776/end-animal-farming-vegetarian-vegan-meat-alternatives-jacy-reese |publisher=Vox}}</ref> Near the end of the book, Reese concludes that, \u201cif I had to speculate, I would say by 2100 all forms of farming will seem outdated and barbaric.\u201d<ref name=\"Kirkus\">{{cite web|title=The End of Animal Farming| publisher=Kirkus Reviews| accessdate=25 August 2018 |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jacy-reese/the-end-of-animal-farming/}}</ref><ref name=\"Robinson\">{{cite web|last=Robinson |first=Nathan |date=12 November 2018 |title=Can we end animal farming forever? |url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2018/11/can-we-end-animal-farming-forever |publisher=Current Affairs}}</ref><ref name=\"Piper\" />\n\n==Publications==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n=== Books ===\n*  Reese, Jacy; ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'' (Beacon Press, 2018)<ref name=\"Publisher's Marketplace\" /><ref name=\"Jacy Reese\">{{cite web|title=Jacy Reese| accessdate=29 December 2017 |url=http://jacyreese.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles ===\n* {{cite news |last=Reese |first=Jacy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/food/2018/nov/16/theres-no-such-thing-as-humane-meat-or-eggs-stop-kidding-yourself |title=There's no such thing as humane meat or eggs. Stop kidding yourself |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 November 2018}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/11/clean-meat-the-future-of-vegetarianism/|title=\u2018Clean Meat,\u2019 the Future of Vegetarianism|last=Reese|first=Jacy|date=6 November 2018|work=[[National Review]]}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=Allison|last2=Reese|first2=Jacy|date=24 March 2016|title=An empirical perspective on animal advocacy.|url=https://animalstudiesrepository.org/animsent/vol1/iss7/12/|volume=1|issue=7|pages=12|work=Animal Sentience}}\n* {{cite news |last=Reese |first=Jacy |url=https://www.salon.com/2016/02/13/this_animal_doesnt_want_to_die_please_think_about_not_eating_him_for_dinner/ |title=The moral demand for cultured meat |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=13 February 2016}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/14/9873012/wild-animals-suffering|title=Wild animals endure illness, injury, and starvation. We should help.|last=Reese|first=Jacy|date=14 December 2015|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reese, Jacy}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American food writers]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American social scientist}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name               = Jacy Reese\n| image              = Jacy Reese.jpg\n| caption            = Reese speaking at the [[University of Oslo]] in 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|12|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Huntsville, Texas|Huntsville]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Texas at Austin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jacyreese.com/assets/downloads/cv.pdf|title=Jacy Reese Curriculum Vitae|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| partner            = Kelly Witwicki\n| relatives          = \n| occupation         = Writer\n}}\n\n'''Jacy Reese''' ({{IPAc-en|'|d\u0292|e\u026a|s|i\u02d0|_|\u02c8|r|i\u02d0|s}})<ref name=\"Animals and The Far Future\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NTV81NZSuKw|title=Animals and the Far Future|website=Youtube|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>; born December 16, 1992) is a writer, social scientist, and co-founder of Sentience Institute. He previously worked as a Senior Fellow at [[Sentience Politics]], and before that at [[Animal Charity Evaluators]] as chair of the board of directors and then as a full-time researcher.\n\nHis research focuses on [[effective altruism]], [[Speciesism|anti-speciesism]], and [[plant-based]] and [[cellular agriculture]]. Reese was recognized as one of [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]\u2019s \u201cHumans of the Year\u201d in December 2017 along with his co-founder Kelly Witwicki.<ref name=\"Gault 1\">{{cite web|last=Gault |first=Matthew |date=28 December 2017 |title=This Think Tank Wants to End Factory Farming |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/ev5v9n/this-think-tanks-wants-to-end-factory-farming |publisher=Vice Motherboard}}</ref> His book, ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'', argues that animal farming will end by 2100.\n\n==Career==\nBefore he graduated from college, Reese was working on the [[Animal Charity Evaluators]] Board of Directors and then joined as a full-time researcher after graduation.<ref name=\"Livegan\">{{cite podcast |last1=Lahey |first1=Kevin |last2=Le Roi |first2=Ben |title=Livegan |date=12 December 2017|time=1:20|url=https://www.buzzsprout.com/128075/609587-e8-jacy-reese |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Animal Charity Evaluators (ACE, formerly called Effective Animal Activism) is an organization within the [[effective altruism]] movement that evaluates and compares various animal charities based on their cost-effectiveness and transparency, particularly those that are tackling [[factory farming]].<ref name=\"auto\">Daniel Engber, [http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2016/08/animal_activists_crunched_the_numbers_to_learn_that_the_creature_most_in.html \"Save the Chicken\"], ''Slate'', August 18, 2016.</ref> While at ACE, Reese published an article that addressed the issue of [[wild animal suffering]], arguing that humans should act on behalf of wild animals to alleviate their suffering if it can be done safely and effectively.<ref name=\"Reese 2\">{{cite web|last=Reese |first=Jacy |date=14 December 2015 |title=Wild animals endure illness, injury, and starvation. We should help. |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/14/9873012/wild-animals-suffering |publisher=Vox}}</ref> His 2015 [[Vox (website)|Vox]] article on the topic was criticized by writers who argued we shouldn't intervene or that we should instead focus on helping domestic animals.<ref name=\"Gunther\">{{cite web|last=Gunther |first=Kristen |date=15 December 2015 |title=Nature is Violent |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/qkjpwp/nature-is-violent/ |publisher=Motherboard}}</ref><ref name=\"Matthews\">{{cite web|last=Matthews |first=Susan |date=16 December 2015 |title=Nature Can't Exist Without Suffering\u2014And We Can't Change That |url=http://www.audubon.org/news/nature-cant-exist-without-suffering-and-we-cant-change |publisher=Audubon}}</ref><ref name=\"McGrath\">{{cite web|last=McGrath |first=Lauren-Elizabeth |date=16 December 2015 |title=Vox Fails to Mention 56 Billion Lives in Piece on Animal Suffering |url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2015/12/16/animal-charity-evaluators-representative-forgets-to-mention-56-billion-animals-when-discussing-animal-suffering-and-deaths/ |publisher=Ecorazzi}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year and a half at Animal Charity Evaluators, Reese briefly worked with [[Sentience Politics]], a project of the Effective Altruism Foundation. Sentience Politics then split into two organizations, one of which was Sentience Institute, co-founded by Reese and his now-fianc\u00e9e Kelly Witwicki in June 2017.<ref name=\"Livegan\" /><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 August 2018 |title=Introducing Sentience Institute |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/blog/introducing-sentience-institute |last1=Witwicki |first1=Kelly |last2=Reese |first2=Jacy|publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref> Sentience Institute is an [[effective altruism]] think tank working to understand and facilitate the expansion of humanity's \"moral circle\" to all sentient beings. They have published research reports including a study of the British [[antislavery]] movement, a study of the French [[nuclear power]] movement, a study of [[genetically modified food]], and a poll of American attitudes towards \u201canimal farming and animal-free food.\u201d<ref name=\"Gault 1\" /><ref name=\"Sentience Institute - Research\">{{cite web|accessdate=29 December 2017 |title=Research |url=https://www.sentienceinstitute.org/research |publisher=Sentience Institute}}</ref><ref name=\"Gault 2\">{{cite web|last=Gault |first=Matthew |date=16 November 2018 |title=Jacy Reese Thinks Technology and Ethics Will See the \u2018End of Animal Farming\u2019 |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/vbavgm/jacy-reese-thinks-technology-and-ethics-will-see-the-end-of-animal-farming |publisher=Vice Motherboard}}</ref> The poll was done in collaboration with [[Ipsos|Ipsos Group]] and found that 47% of Americans support \u201ca ban on slaughterhouses.\u201d<ref name=\"Chiorando\">{{cite web|last=Chiorando |first=Maria |date=20 November 2017 |title=Poll Shows 47% Of Americans 'Agree With Ban On Slaughterhouses' |url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/poll-shows-47-of-americans-agree-with-ban-on-slaughterhouses |publisher=Plant Based News}}</ref><ref name=\"Starostinetskaya 2\">{{cite web|last=Starostinetskaya |first=Anna |date=21 November 2017 |title=Nearly Half of Americans Want to Ban Slaughterhouses |url=http://vegnews.com/articles/page.do?pageId=7509&catId=1 |publisher=VegNews}}</ref><ref name=\"Neff\">{{cite web|last=Neff |first=Michelle |date=21 November 2017 |title=New Poll Reveals Nearly 50% of Americans Want to Ban Slaughterhouses and Would Prefer Animal-Free Meat |url=http://www.onegreenplanet.org/news/americans-want-to-ban-slaughterhouses/ |publisher=One Green Planet}}</ref><ref name=\"Ettinger\">{{cite web|last=Ettinger |first=Jill |date=21 November 2017 |title=70% of Americans Want Better Treatment for Farm Animals, Poll Finds |url=http://www.organicauthority.com/70-of-americans-want-better-treatment-for-farm-animals-poll-finds/ |publisher=Organic Authority}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'', Reese \"outlines an evidence-based roadmap to a humane, ethical, efficient food system where slaughterhouses are obsolete\".<ref name=\"Spector\">{{cite web|last=Spector |first=Nicole |date=1 March 2017 |title=Fowl play? Subway denies its chicken is only 50% real |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/34634185/fowl-play-subway-denies-its-chicken-is-only-50-real |publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Publisher's Marketplace\">{{cite web|title=Dealmaker: Beacon Press (Imprint)| publisher=Publishers Marketplace| accessdate=29 December 2017 |url=https://www.publishersmarketplace.com/dealmakers/detail.cgi?id=2264}}</ref> Reese wrote this book from the perspective of [[effective altruism]] because there is already much content explaining the problems of animal agriculture, but he perceived a need for a book to guide the \"farmed animal movement\" towards its long-term goal.<ref name=\"Piper\">{{cite web|last=Piper |first=Kelsey |date=15 November 2018 |title=We could end factory farming this century |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2018/11/15/18088776/end-animal-farming-vegetarian-vegan-meat-alternatives-jacy-reese |publisher=Vox}}</ref> Near the end of the book, Reese concludes that, \u201cif I had to speculate, I would say by 2100 all forms of farming will seem outdated and barbaric.\u201d<ref name=\"Kirkus\">{{cite web|title=The End of Animal Farming| publisher=Kirkus Reviews| accessdate=25 August 2018 |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/jacy-reese/the-end-of-animal-farming/}}</ref><ref name=\"Robinson\">{{cite web|last=Robinson |first=Nathan |date=12 November 2018 |title=Can we end animal farming forever? |url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2018/11/can-we-end-animal-farming-forever |publisher=Current Affairs}}</ref><ref name=\"Piper\" />\n\n==Publications==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n=== Books ===\n*  Reese, Jacy; ''[[The End of Animal Farming]]'' (Beacon Press, 2018)<ref name=\"Publisher's Marketplace\" /><ref name=\"Jacy Reese\">{{cite web|title=Jacy Reese| accessdate=29 December 2017 |url=http://jacyreese.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles ===\n* {{cite news |last=Reese |first=Jacy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/food/2018/nov/16/theres-no-such-thing-as-humane-meat-or-eggs-stop-kidding-yourself |title=There's no such thing as humane meat or eggs. Stop kidding yourself |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 November 2018}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2018/11/clean-meat-the-future-of-vegetarianism/|title=\u2018Clean Meat,\u2019 the Future of Vegetarianism|last=Reese|first=Jacy|date=6 November 2018|work=[[National Review]]}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Smith|first1=Allison|last2=Reese|first2=Jacy|date=24 March 2016|title=An empirical perspective on animal advocacy.|url=https://animalstudiesrepository.org/animsent/vol1/iss7/12/|volume=1|issue=7|pages=12|work=Animal Sentience}}\n* {{cite news |last=Reese |first=Jacy |url=https://www.salon.com/2016/02/13/this_animal_doesnt_want_to_die_please_think_about_not_eating_him_for_dinner/ |title=The moral demand for cultured meat |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=13 February 2016}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/12/14/9873012/wild-animals-suffering|title=Wild animals endure illness, injury, and starvation. We should help.|last=Reese|first=Jacy|date=14 December 2015|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reese, Jacy}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American food writers]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:Animal rights scholars]]\n[[Category:Diet food advocates]]\n[[Category:Veganism]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "name_user": "WeyerStudentOfAgrippa", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacy_Reese"}
{"title_page": "Wolver Hollow", "text_new": "{{short description|British Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Wolver Hollow\n| image = Owner_Mrs_C_Iselin.svg\n| caption = Colours of [[Hope Goddard Iselin|Mrs C. O. Iselin]]\n| sire = Sovereign Path\n| grandsire = [[Grey Sovereign]]\n| dam = Cygnet\n| damsire = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]]\n| sex = [[Stallion (horse)|Stallion]]\n| foaled = 1964\n| country =  [[United Kingdom]]\n| colour = [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = \n| owner = [[Hope Goddard Iselin]]\n| trainer = [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]]<br>[[Henry Cecil]]\n| record = 20: 4-5-3\n| earnings = \u00a340,546\n| race = [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1969)\n| awards = [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland]] (1976)\n| honours =  [[Timeform|Timeform rating]]: 126 \n| updated= \n}}\n'''Wolver Hollow''' (1964\u20131987) was a British-bred [[Thoroughbred]] [[Horse racing|racehorse]] and stallion. In a career spanning four seasons, his performances in handicaps and top class company, including victory in the 1969 [[Eclipse Stakes]], established him as a talented racehorse without being exceptional. He would achieve greater success as a stallion whereupon retiring to stud where he became [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland|Champion Sire]] in Britain.\n\n==Background==\n\nBy Sovereign Path and out of Cygnet, Wolver Hollow was sold as a yearling, fetching 4,000 guineas<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, 14. The Times Digital Archive (accessed April 3, 2020).</ref> Sovereign Path, rated 125 by [[Timeform]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=701}}</ref> was successful in the 1959 [[Tetrarch Stakes]] as well as the 1960 renewals of the [[Lockinge Stakes]] and [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]. As a sire, he produced sixteen crops of racehorses, the most notable of which was [[Humble Duty]]. Nevertheless, he also counted multiple big race winners among his progeny including Town Crier ([[Queen Anne Stakes]]), Supreme Sovereign ([[Lockinge Stakes]]) and Spanish Express ([[Middle Park Stakes]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=936}}</ref>. While Wolver Hollow's dam Cygnet, by undefeated champion racehorse [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]], did not hail from an immediately prolific family, her third dam, Sunshot, was the granddam of classic winners Resplendent (1926 [[Irish Oaks]] and dam of [[Windsor Lad]]) and Sol Speranza who won the same two classics in 1937.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1943 |title=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |url= |journal=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |volume=32 |issue= |pages=73 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> Alongside Wolver Hollow, Cygnet produced nine other foals including Gaybrook Swan, second in the 1970 [[Northern Dancer Turf Stakes|Niagara Handicap]] and Tall Dream, runner up in both the [[Vincent O'Brien National Stakes|National Stakes]] and [[Beresford Stakes]] of 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodstockreports.co.uk/weatherbys/wbr/orderreports/orderReportParameters.jsp?listSection=FR&listSectionName=Free%20Reports&countryCode=GB&optNo=79&priceId=1 |title=Weatherbys Bloodstock Reports |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://galopp-sieger.de/galoppsieger/pferd_html?pschl=Tall%20DreamTamerlane |title=Gallop Sieger |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===1966: two-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made his debut in the 1966 New Stakes, now known as the [[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|Norfolk Stakes]], at Ascot where he finished four lengths behind the Johnson Houghton trained Falcon.<ref>FROM OUR RACING CORRESPONDENT. \"Fighting Charlie falters but wins easily.\" Times, June 17, 1966, 5.</ref> On his second start, he finished behind Falcon again when fourth in the [[National Stakes (Sandown Park)|National Stakes]] at Sandown<ref>\"Sandown Park Details\" Times, 21 July 1966, p. 5.</ref> - a course incidentally where Falcon would win the following season's [[Temple Stakes]]. Wolver Hollow would then be unplaced at Kempton before rounding off the season finishing fourth of thirteen starters in the [[Dewhurst Stakes]] behind the next season's English and Irish Derby third Dart Board.\n\n===1967: three-year-old season===\nNewbury would be Wolver Hollow's first port of call in 1967 where he would contest the [[Greenham Stakes]], a traditional trial for the [[2000 Guineas]]. Finishing third by a neck and a head, this was the closest he had come to shedding his maiden tag. However, it was not the strongest Guineas trial given that neither of the front two were entered for the classic.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Classic horses not impressive.\" Times, April 24, 1967, 12.</ref> While it transpired to be useful form, (the runner up,[[Reform (horse)|Reform]], would become the leading miler of the season), Wolver Hollow started at an unfancied 40/1 when finishing unplaced on his next start in the Guineas.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Royal Palace beats milers at their own game.\" Times, May 4, 1967, 13.</ref> Returning to the Royal Ascot meeting where he made his debut the previous year, Wolver Hollow again ran into Reform finishing just under a length and a half fourth in the [[St James's Palace Stakes]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Steeple Aston can go one better in Hunt Cup.\" Times, 21 June 1967, p. 11.</ref> At the Goodwood meeting, Wolver Hollow entered handicap company with a reasonable fifth under second top-weight, giving a pound to Irish Derby runner up Sucaryl and six pounds to [[Falmouth Stakes]] winner Resilience.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Hopes vanish as Caergwrle heads for Midhurst.\" Times, 29 July 1967, p. 14.</ref> A step down in class a month later facilitated Wolver Hollow finally losing his maiden tag as he won the ten furlong Virginia Stakes at Newcastle. While the contest was effectively a maiden race, Wolver Hollow only had to be shaken up to win by four lengths.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Northern Racing.\" Times, August 29, 1967, 11.</ref> Little over a week later, Wolver Hollow doubled his tally with success in the one mile Crathorne Sweepstakes at York. There he faced three rivals;- Worthy Friend, a long priced outsider, [[Epsom Derby|Derby]] also-ran Scottish Sinbad who won a handicap at the same Newcastle meeting where Wolver Hollow was victorious, and [[Queen Anne Stakes]] runner up Arenaria who was in receipt of ten pounds.<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Scottish Sinbad is best choice.\" Times, 7 Sept. 1967, p. 14.</ref> Scottish Sinbad made the running but was closely tracked by Wolver Hollow under a motionless Edward Hide who sent his mount home inside the final furlong to win by a length and a half with Arenaria a further two lengths behind. After the race, he was given a 25/1 quote for the [[Cambridgeshire Handicap]].<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, p. 14.</ref> In preparation for the Cambridgeshire, Wolver Hollow contested the Wavertree Stakes at Newmarket but was unable to complete a hat-trick, finishing a length and three quarters behind easy [[Nassau Stakes]] winner Fair Winter.<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 18, 1967, p. 11.</ref> Wolver Hollow capped off his season with a two and a half length third in the Cambridgeshire off 8st 12lb behind [[Irish 1,000 Guineas]] winner Lacquer<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 28, 1967, p. 12.</ref>\n\n===1968: four-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made four racecourse appearances in 1968 although the first was not until August when he participated in two races at the Deauville summer festival. The first appearance came when fourth in the [[Prix Gontaut-Biron]] won by Frontal - himself fourth in the previous season's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. On ground considered too soft for him, he was squeezed out of third by a head by Grandier who went on to win a [[Prix d'Ispahan]] and a [[Prix Ganay]] as well as finish third in a [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Rehearsal for Hopeful Venture.\" Times, 26 Aug. 1968, p. 12.</ref> Nine days later, Wolver Hollow ventured into calmer waters when winning the Prix Ridgway from Right Honourable and Atopolis. <ref>PAR, R. R. \"\" WOLVER HOLLOW \"REMPORTE LE PRIX RIDGWAY.\" Le Monde, 28 Aug. 1968.</ref> After a scheduled run at Newbury was cancelled following the abandonment of the meeting, Wolver Hollow's next run was in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]<ref>\"Racing Results.\" Times, 16 Sept. 1968, p. 12.</ref>. The absences of [[2000 Guineas]] third Jimmy Reppin and [[Irish Derby]] runner up Ribofilio notwithstanding, the field still featured [[Sussex Stakes]] runner up World Cup, [[Prix Jean Prat]] victor [[Lorenzaccio (horse)|Lorenzaccio]] and [[Greenham Stakes]] winner Heathen.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Lorenzaccio can hold off World Cup.\" Times, September 28, 1968, p. 6.</ref> The race, ran on soft ground, was contested between World Cup and Wolver Hollow up the straight with the former eventually winning by four easy lengths with Lorenzaccio a further three lengths behind in third.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"World Cup Scores Despite Rumours.\" The Observer, Sep 29, 1968.</ref> Wolver Hollow's season would culminate once again in the Cambridgeshire Handicap, this time shouldering top weight of 9st 8lbs. Next in the weights was [[Diadem Stakes]] winner Secret Ray on 9st 6lbs, [[Jersey Stakes]] third Paddy Me on 9st 4lbs, the same weight as previous year's runner up Straight Master while [[Yorkshire Oaks]] winner Exchange, carrying 9st, was sent off favourite.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Sir Ivor has stamina to win 'Champion'.\" Times, 19 Oct. 1968, p. 7.</ref> Wolver Hollow ran a career best to finish second, going down by a neck to Emirilo despite conceding twenty-seven pounds.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Great win for Sir Ivor at Newmarket.\" Times, 21 Oct. 1968, p. 11.</ref>\n\n===1969: five-year-old season===\n[[Henry Cecil|Henry Cecil's]] first season as a racehorse trainer would be spearheaded by Wolver Hollow's final season as a racehorse. His reappearance came in the Mark Lane Jubilee Stakes, a ten furlong handicap over ten furlongs on very soft ground. There he faced a stiff task sitting on top of the handicap conceding upwards of seven pounds to winners of the [[Rosebery Stakes]] and the [[City and Suburban Handicap]] along with the previous year's winner.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Wolver Hollow can survive stern test.\" Times, May 10, 1969, 6.</ref> In the event, bottom weight Sovereign Ruler won by a facile eight lengths and would go on to win two and twice finish placed in valuable handicaps through the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=671}}</ref> Wolver Hollow finished runner up while conceding thirty-five pounds to the well handicapped winner and was very much considered a contender going into the [[Lockinge Stakes]] on his next start.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Jimmy Reppin may take Lockinge Stakes.\" Times, 31 May 1969, p. 6.</ref> However, he would finish a tailed off last of six behind [[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]] and subsequently underwent a dope test.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Lockinge Goes to Habitat.\" The Observer, Jun 01, 1969. P. 21.</ref> Wolver Hollow's penultimate start came at Royal Ascot in the [[Prince of Wales's Stakes]] where he would be ridden by [[Lester Piggot]] for the first time. Here he faced four rivals in the shape of [[Noel Murless|Noel Murless's]] top class [[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]], [[Epsom Derby]] also-ran Stoned and a couple of high class handicappers.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Prince Tenderfoot may be too fast for rivals.\" Times, 17 June 1969, p. 13.</ref> Class told with Connaught making all to win by five lengths ahead of Wolver Hollow, with stoned a further two lengths behind in third.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Double for Barclay.\" Times, June 18, 1969, 13.</ref> Wolver Hollow's career would be defined by his final start in the [[Eclipse Stakes]] where he would also be the last horse to carry his owner's colours.<ref name=\"auto1\">BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Big Prize for Last Runner.\" The Observer (1901- 2003), Jul 06, 1969, p. 19.</ref> Coughing forced Connaught and Ribofilio (Irish Derby second) to miss their engagement while the useful Remand was withdrawn leaving seven runners to face the starter at Sandown. High class continental form was well represented with Light Wind, who had won that season's [[Premio Presidente della Repubblica]], Hogarth who won the 1968 [[Derby Italiano]] and Timmy My Boy who finished runner up in that year's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. Royal Rocket was third in the [[Brigadier Gerard Stakes|Coronation Stakes]] while sole three year old runner Rocked finished third in the [[Greenham Stakes]]. Park Top, bidding to become the first mare to win in the race's history, came into the race three from three for the season collecting the Prix de la Seine, the [[Coronation Cup]] and the [[Hardwicke Stakes]] along the way.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=509}}</ref>. Waiting tactics were typically employed on Park Top and controversially, this would be her undoing in the race. As described in Timeform's Racehorses of 1969 \"Wolver Hollow turned for home behind Park Top, came up the rails, gradually made his way to the front after an uninterrupted run, and led throughout the last furlong to win comfortably. Park Top, on the other hand, had several positions in the straight. She ran into the heels of the pacemaking Rocked two furlongs out, and after making her way round that horse she found her way blocked by the Italian Derby winner Hogarth. By the time she had moved out to come round Hogarth on the wide outside she had no chance of catching Wolver Hollow: she had used up most of her energy finding a way through, and courage wasn't enough to win her the prize.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=510}}</ref> Park Top would win the [[King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Stakes]] next time under Lester Piggot, confirming that she was superior to her Sandown showing. Nevertheless, Wolver Hollow's win was enough to secure a new career as a stallion.\n\n==Races==\n\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" style=\" text-align:centre; margin-left:1em; float:centre ;border-collapse: collapse; font-size:100%\"\n|-  style=\"background:#dacaa4; text-align:center;\"\n!'''Date'''\n!'''Finish'''\n!'''Race'''\n!'''Dist'''\n!'''Jockey'''\n!'''Winner/Runner up '''\n!'''Track'''\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|06|16}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|New Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|07|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[National_Stakes_(Sandown_Park)|National Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|09|17}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|Imperial Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">6</span>6f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Heath Rose\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|10|14}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Dewhurst Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Dart Board\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|04|22}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Greenham Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Play High\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|05|03}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|[[2000 Guineas Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Doug Smith  (jockey)|Doug Smith ]]\n|[[Royal_Palace_(horse)|Royal Palace]]\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|06|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[St James's Palace Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[George Moore (jockey)|George Moore]]\n|[[Reform (horse)|Reform]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|07|28}}\t\n|5th\n|News of the World Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sucaryl\n|[[Goodwood Racecourse|Goodwood]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|08|28}}\t\n|1st\n|Virginia Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Future Fame\n|[[Newcastle Racecourse|Newcastle]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|07}}\t\n|1st\n|Crathorne Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Scottish Sinbad\n|[[York Racecourse|York]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|16}}\t\n|3rd\n|Wavertree Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Fair Winter\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|10|21}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Lacquer\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|17}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Prix Gontaut-Biron]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Frontal\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|26}}\t\n|1st\n|Prix Ridgway\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Right Honourable\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|9|28}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|World Cup\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|10|19}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Emerilo\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|10}}\t\n|2nd\n|Jubilee Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sovereign Ruler\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|31}}\t\n|6th\n|[[Lockinge Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|[[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]]\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|6|17}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Prince of Wales's Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|7|5}}\t\n|1st\n|[[Eclipse Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Park Top]]\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Stud career==\nWhen owner [[Hope Goddard Iselin]] retired at the age of 102, the horses she still had in training were sent to be sold at Newmarket. The one exception was Wolver Hollow who was given to his former trainer [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On Wolver Hollow's retirement, he was syndicated by the Curragh Bloodstock Agency and initially stood at Athgarvan Stud, The Curragh.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=999}}</ref> Through a friendship between Boyd-Rochfort and Billy Iceton, Wolver Hollow spent his latter breeding career at Tara Stud in County Meath.<ref>Griffiths, Richard. \"Tributes paid after death of renowned stud master Billy Iceton, aged 81.\" Racing Post, May 20, 2010: 17.</ref> Wolver Hollow enjoyed success with his first crop, spearheaded by the classic winning [[Furry Glen]]. His greatest achievement as a stallion came in 1976 when the Henry Cecil trained [[Wollow]] won five top class races, enabling his sire to become the leading sire in the UK and Ireland. Wollow's contribution to this achievement can not be understated. Wolver Hollow earned his accolade with a record of 34 wins from 18 horses amassing \u00a3192,362 in prize money - \u00a3166,389 of which was won by Wollow. Indeed, Wollow's earnings were such that they eclipsed the \u00a3166,323 earned by the progeny of [[Vaguely Noble]], that season's second leading sire.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=825}}</ref> Unsurprisingly, this would represent the zenith of Wolver Hollow's stallion career and while he would produce a further handful of useful horses, none of them would win at the highest level. \n\nAs a damsire, Wolver Hollow could not count any European Group One winners among his descendants although Love A Show was victorious in the 1983 [[Blue Diamond Stakes]]. Other horses of note include Reach, winner of the 1984 [[Royal Lodge Stakes]], Festive Cheer, third in the 1991 [[Phoenix Stakes]], Treasure Hope, winner of the 1992 [[Premio Regina Elena]] (Italian 1000 Guineas), and Wrapping, a runner up in the 1989 [[Oaks d'Italia]]. Wolver Hollow was also the damsire of several useful [[National Hunt]] horses such as Simply Dashing, a high class handicap chaser who finished second in a [[Charlie Hall Chase]], 1992 [[Baring Bingham Novices' Hurdle]] winner Thetford Forest and useful handicapper Latent Talent. \n\nHe was euthanised due to deteriorating health on 13 June 1987.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedigreequery.com/wolver+hollow|title=Wolver Hollow Horse Pedigree|website=www.pedigreequery.com}}</ref>\n\n===Notable progeny===\n\n''c = [[colt (horse)|colt]], f = [[filly]], g = [[gelding]]''\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse\" font-size:80%\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Foaled'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Name'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Dam'''\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Sex'''\n| style=\"width:510px;\"| '''Major Wins and Notable Performances'''\n|-\n| 1971\n| Charlie Bubbles\n| Sixandahalf\n| c\n| 1st [[Hardwicke Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| [[Furry Glen]]\n| Cleftess\n| c\n| 1st [[Marble Hill Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Leopardstown Stakes|Mullion Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Irish 2000 Guineas]] (1974) 1st [[International Stakes (Ireland)|Whitehall Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Vauxhall Trial Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Gallinule Stakes]] (1974) 3rd [[Coventry Stakes]] (1973) 3rd Larkspur Stakes (1973) \n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| Wanlockhead\n| Exultation\n| c\n| 3rd [[Gordon Richards Stakes|Westbury Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| [[Wollow]]\n| Wichuraiana\n| c\n| 1st [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Dewhurst Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Greenham Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[2000 Guineas]] (1976) 1st [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[Sussex Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[International Stakes|Benson & Hedges Gold Cup]] (1976)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| Wolverlife\n| Miralife\n| c\n| 3rd [[Duke of York Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Palace House Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Diamond Jubilee Stakes|Cork and Orrery Stakes]]\n|-\n|-\n| 1975\n| My Hollow\n| Saucy Mine\n| f\n| 1st [[Royal Whip Stakes]] (1980) 1st [[Desmond Stakes]] (1980) 2nd [[Blandford Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Galaxy Libra\n| Garden of Eden\n| c\n| 1st [[Man o' War Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Joe Hirsch Turf Classic Invitational Stakes]] (1981) 3rd [[Charles Whittingham Stakes|Hollywood Invitational Handicap]] (1981) 3rd [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] (1981)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Wolverton\n| Mary Murphy\n| c\n| 1st [[Prix Daniel Wildenstein|Prix du Rond-Point]] (1979) 1st [[Prix Edmond Blanc]] (1980) 2nd [[Prix Greffulhe]] (1979)\n|-\n|-\n| 1977\n| Gift Wrapped\n| Doc Nan\n| f\n| 1st [[Lingfield Oaks Trial]] (1980) 2nd [[Musidora Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Sun Chariot Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Hays\n| Sing A Song\n| c\n| 1st [[Mill Reef Stakes]] (1981) 1st [[2,000 Guineas Trial Stakes]] (1982) 2nd [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Hungerford Stakes]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Teofane\n| The Yellow Girl\n| c\n| 2nd [[Derby Italiano]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1980\n| Sherbaz\n| Shelina\n| c\n| 3rd [[Prix La Rochette]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1981\n| Gamelion\n| Glamingo\n| g\n| 1st Prix des Drags (1986)\n|-\n|-\n| 1983\n| Hollow Hand\n| Fingers\n| c\n| 2nd [[Horris Hill Stakes]] (1985)\n|-\n|}\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Wolver Hollow (GB), bay horse, 1964<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = Sovereign Path (GB)<br />1956\n|m = Cygnet (GB)<br />1950\n|ff = [[Grey Sovereign]] (GB)<br />1948\n|fm = Mountain Path (GB)<br />1948\n|mf = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]] (FR)<br />1942\n|mm = Mrs. Swan Song (IRE)<br />1940\n|fff = [[Nasrullah (horse)|Nasrullah]]\n|ffm = Kong\n|fmf = Bobsleigh\n|fmm = Path Of Peace\n|mff = [[Tourbillon (horse)|Tourbillon]]\n|mfm = Astronomie\n|mmf = Sir Walter Raleigh\n|mmm = Donati's Comet\n|ffff = [[Nearco]]\n|fffm = Mumtaz Begum\n|ffmf = Baytown\n|ffmm = Clang\n|fmff = [[Gainsborough (horse)|Gainsborough]]\n|fmfm = Toboggan\n|fmmf = Winalot\n|fmmm = Grand Peace\n|mfff = [[Ksar (horse)|Ksar]]\n|mffm = Durban\n|mfmf = Asterus\n|mfmm = Likka\n|mmff = Prince Galahad\n|mmfm = Smoke Lass\n|mmmf = Flying Orb\n|mmmm = Sunshot\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKvNyOYoSS0 1969 Eclipse Stakes] (YouTube)\n\n[[Category:1964 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:1987 racehorse deaths]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 19-b]]\n[[Category:British Champion Thoroughbred Sires]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Wolver Hollow\n| image = Owner_Mrs_C_Iselin.svg\n| caption = Colours of [[Hope Goddard Iselin|Mrs C. O. Iselin]]\n| sire = Sovereign Path\n| grandsire = [[Grey Sovereign]]\n| dam = Cygnet\n| damsire = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]]\n| sex = [[Stallion (horse)|Stallion]]\n| foaled = 1964\n| country =  [[United Kingdom]]\n| colour = [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = \n| owner = [[Hope Goddard Iselin]]\n| trainer = [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]]<br>[[Henry Cecil]]\n| record = 20: 4-5-3\n| earnings = \u00a340,546\n| race = [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1969)\n| awards = [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland]] (1976)\n| honours =  [[Timeform|Timeform rating]]: 126 \n| updated= \n}}\n'''Wolver Hollow''' (1964\u20131987) was a British-bred [[Thoroughbred]] [[Horse racing|racehorse]] and stallion. In a career spanning four seasons, his performances in handicaps and top class company, including victory in the 1969 [[Eclipse Stakes]], established him as a talented racehorse without being exceptional. He would achieve greater success as a stallion whereupon retiring to stud where he became [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland|Champion Sire]] in Britain.\n\n==Background==\n\nBy Sovereign Path and out of Cygnet, Wolver Hollow was sold as a yearling, fetching 4,000 guineas<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, 14. The Times Digital Archive (accessed April 3, 2020).</ref> Sovereign Path, rated 125 by [[Timeform]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=701}}</ref> was successful in the 1959 [[Tetrarch Stakes]] as well as the 1960 renewals of the [[Lockinge Stakes]] and [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]. As a sire, he produced sixteen crops of racehorses, the most notable of which was [[Humble Duty]]. Nevertheless, he also counted multiple big race winners among his progeny including Town Crier ([[Queen Anne Stakes]]), Supreme Sovereign ([[Lockinge Stakes]]) and Spanish Express ([[Middle Park Stakes]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=936}}</ref>. While Wolver Hollow's dam Cygnet, by undefeated champion racehorse [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]], did not hail from an immediately prolific family, her third dam, Sunshot, was the granddam of classic winners Resplendent (1926 [[Irish Oaks]] and dam of [[Windsor Lad]]) and Sol Speranza who won the same two classics in 1937.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1943 |title=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |url= |journal=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |volume=32 |issue= |pages=73 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> Alongside Wolver Hollow, Cygnet produced nine other foals including Gaybrook Swan, second in the 1970 [[Northern Dancer Turf Stakes|Niagara Handicap]] and Tall Dream, runner up in both the [[Vincent O'Brien National Stakes|National Stakes]] and [[Beresford Stakes]] of 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodstockreports.co.uk/weatherbys/wbr/orderreports/orderReportParameters.jsp?listSection=FR&listSectionName=Free%20Reports&countryCode=GB&optNo=79&priceId=1 |title=Weatherbys Bloodstock Reports |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://galopp-sieger.de/galoppsieger/pferd_html?pschl=Tall%20DreamTamerlane |title=Gallop Sieger |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===1966: two-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made his debut in the 1966 New Stakes, now known as the [[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|Norfolk Stakes]], at Ascot where he finished four lengths behind the Johnson Houghton trained Falcon.<ref>FROM OUR RACING CORRESPONDENT. \"Fighting Charlie falters but wins easily.\" Times, June 17, 1966, 5.</ref> On his second start, he finished behind Falcon again when fourth in the [[National Stakes (Sandown Park)|National Stakes]] at Sandown<ref>\"Sandown Park Details\" Times, 21 July 1966, p. 5.</ref> - a course incidentally where Falcon would win the following season's [[Temple Stakes]]. Wolver Hollow would then be unplaced at Kempton before rounding off the season finishing fourth of thirteen starters in the [[Dewhurst Stakes]] behind the next season's English and Irish Derby third Dart Board.\n\n===1967: three-year-old season===\nNewbury would be Wolver Hollow's first port of call in 1967 where he would contest the [[Greenham Stakes]], a traditional trial for the [[2000 Guineas]]. Finishing third by a neck and a head, this was the closest he had come to shedding his maiden tag. However, it was not the strongest Guineas trial given that neither of the front two were entered for the classic.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Classic horses not impressive.\" Times, April 24, 1967, 12.</ref> While it transpired to be useful form, (the runner up,[[Reform (horse)|Reform]], would become the leading miler of the season), Wolver Hollow started at an unfancied 40/1 when finishing unplaced on his next start in the Guineas.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Royal Palace beats milers at their own game.\" Times, May 4, 1967, 13.</ref> Returning to the Royal Ascot meeting where he made his debut the previous year, Wolver Hollow again ran into Reform finishing just under a length and a half fourth in the [[St James's Palace Stakes]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Steeple Aston can go one better in Hunt Cup.\" Times, 21 June 1967, p. 11.</ref> At the Goodwood meeting, Wolver Hollow entered handicap company with a reasonable fifth under second top-weight, giving a pound to Irish Derby runner up Sucaryl and six pounds to [[Falmouth Stakes]] winner Resilience.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Hopes vanish as Caergwrle heads for Midhurst.\" Times, 29 July 1967, p. 14.</ref> A step down in class a month later facilitated Wolver Hollow finally losing his maiden tag as he won the ten furlong Virginia Stakes at Newcastle. While the contest was effectively a maiden race, Wolver Hollow only had to be shaken up to win by four lengths.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Northern Racing.\" Times, August 29, 1967, 11.</ref> Little over a week later, Wolver Hollow doubled his tally with success in the one mile Crathorne Sweepstakes at York. There he faced three rivals;- Worthy Friend, a long priced outsider, [[Epsom Derby|Derby]] also-ran Scottish Sinbad who won a handicap at the same Newcastle meeting where Wolver Hollow was victorious, and [[Queen Anne Stakes]] runner up Arenaria who was in receipt of ten pounds.<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Scottish Sinbad is best choice.\" Times, 7 Sept. 1967, p. 14.</ref> Scottish Sinbad made the running but was closely tracked by Wolver Hollow under a motionless Edward Hide who sent his mount home inside the final furlong to win by a length and a half with Arenaria a further two lengths behind. After the race, he was given a 25/1 quote for the [[Cambridgeshire Handicap]].<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, p. 14.</ref> In preparation for the Cambridgeshire, Wolver Hollow contested the Wavertree Stakes at Newmarket but was unable to complete a hat-trick, finishing a length and three quarters behind easy [[Nassau Stakes]] winner Fair Winter.<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 18, 1967, p. 11.</ref> Wolver Hollow capped off his season with a two and a half length third in the Cambridgeshire off 8st 12lb behind [[Irish 1,000 Guineas]] winner Lacquer<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 28, 1967, p. 12.</ref>\n\n===1968: four-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made four racecourse appearances in 1968 although the first was not until August when he participated in two races at the Deauville summer festival. The first appearance came when fourth in the [[Prix Gontaut-Biron]] won by Frontal - himself fourth in the previous season's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. On ground considered too soft for him, he was squeezed out of third by a head by Grandier who went on to win a [[Prix d'Ispahan]] and a [[Prix Ganay]] as well as finish third in a [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Rehearsal for Hopeful Venture.\" Times, 26 Aug. 1968, p. 12.</ref> Nine days later, Wolver Hollow ventured into calmer waters when winning the Prix Ridgway from Right Honourable and Atopolis. <ref>PAR, R. R. \"\" WOLVER HOLLOW \"REMPORTE LE PRIX RIDGWAY.\" Le Monde, 28 Aug. 1968.</ref> After a scheduled run at Newbury was cancelled following the abandonment of the meeting, Wolver Hollow's next run was in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]<ref>\"Racing Results.\" Times, 16 Sept. 1968, p. 12.</ref>. The absences of [[2000 Guineas]] third Jimmy Reppin and [[Irish Derby]] runner up Ribofilio notwithstanding, the field still featured [[Sussex Stakes]] runner up World Cup, [[Prix Jean Prat]] victor Lorenzaccio and [[Greenham Stakes]] winner Heathen.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Lorenzaccio can hold off World Cup.\" Times, September 28, 1968, p. 6.</ref> The race, ran on soft ground, was contested between World Cup and Wolver Hollow up the straight with the former eventually winning by four easy lengths with Lorenzaccio a further three lengths behind in third.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"World Cup Scores Despite Rumours.\" The Observer, Sep 29, 1968.</ref> Wolver Hollow's season would culminate once again in the Cambridgeshire Handicap, this time shouldering top weight of 9st 8lbs. Next in the weights was [[Diadem Stakes]] winner Secret Ray on 9st 6lbs, [[Jersey Stakes]] third Paddy Me on 9st 4lbs, the same weight as previous year's runner up Straight Master while [[Yorkshire Oaks]] winner Exchange, carrying 9st, was sent off favourite.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Sir Ivor has stamina to win 'Champion'.\" Times, 19 Oct. 1968, p. 7.</ref> Wolver Hollow ran a career best to finish second, going down by a neck to Emirilo despite conceding twenty-seven pounds.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Great win for Sir Ivor at Newmarket.\" Times, 21 Oct. 1968, p. 11.</ref>\n\n===1969: five-year-old season===\n[[Henry Cecil|Henry Cecil's]] first season as a racehorse trainer would be spearheaded by Wolver Hollow's final season as a racehorse. His reappearance came in the Mark Lane Jubilee Stakes, a ten furlong handicap over ten furlongs on very soft ground. There he faced a stiff task sitting on top of the handicap conceding upwards of seven pounds to winners of the [[Rosebery Stakes]] and the [[City and Suburban Handicap]] along with the previous year's winner.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Wolver Hollow can survive stern test.\" Times, May 10, 1969, 6.</ref> In the event, bottom weight Sovereign Ruler won by a facile eight lengths and would go on to win two and twice finish placed in valuable handicaps through the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=671}}</ref> Wolver Hollow finished runner up while conceding thirty-five pounds to the well handicapped winner and was very much considered a contender going into the [[Lockinge Stakes]] on his next start.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Jimmy Reppin may take Lockinge Stakes.\" Times, 31 May 1969, p. 6.</ref> However, he would finish a tailed off last of six behind [[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]] and subsequently underwent a dope test.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Lockinge Goes to Habitat.\" The Observer, Jun 01, 1969. P. 21.</ref> Wolver Hollow's penultimate start came at Royal Ascot in the [[Prince of Wales's Stakes]] where he would be ridden by [[Lester Piggot]] for the first time. Here he faced four rivals in the shape of [[Noel Murless|Noel Murless's]] top class [[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]], [[Epsom Derby]] also-ran Stoned and a couple of high class handicappers.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Prince Tenderfoot may be too fast for rivals.\" Times, 17 June 1969, p. 13.</ref> Class told with Connaught making all to win by five lengths ahead of Wolver Hollow, with stoned a further two lengths behind in third.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Double for Barclay.\" Times, June 18, 1969, 13.</ref> Wolver Hollow's career would be defined by his final start in the [[Eclipse Stakes]] where he would also be the last horse to carry his owner's colours.<ref name=\"auto1\">BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Big Prize for Last Runner.\" The Observer (1901- 2003), Jul 06, 1969, p. 19.</ref> Coughing forced Connaught and Ribofilio (Irish Derby second) to miss their engagement while the useful Remand was withdrawn leaving seven runners to face the starter at Sandown. High class continental form was well represented with Light Wind, who had won that season's [[Premio Presidente della Repubblica]], Hogarth who won the 1968 [[Derby Italiano]] and Timmy My Boy who finished runner up in that year's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. Royal Rocket was third in the [[Brigadier Gerard Stakes|Coronation Stakes]] while sole three year old runner Rocked finished third in the [[Greenham Stakes]]. Park Top, bidding to become the first mare to win in the race's history, came into the race three from three for the season collecting the Prix de la Seine, the [[Coronation Cup]] and the [[Hardwicke Stakes]] along the way.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=509}}</ref>. Waiting tactics were typically employed on Park Top and controversially, this would be her undoing in the race. As described in Timeform's Racehorses of 1969 \"Wolver Hollow turned for home behind Park Top, came up the rails, gradually made his way to the front after an uninterrupted run, and led throughout the last furlong to win comfortably. Park Top, on the other hand, had several positions in the straight. She ran into the heels of the pacemaking Rocked two furlongs out, and after making her way round that horse she found her way blocked by the Italian Derby winner Hogarth. By the time she had moved out to come round Hogarth on the wide outside she had no chance of catching Wolver Hollow: she had used up most of her energy finding a way through, and courage wasn't enough to win her the prize.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=510}}</ref> Park Top would win the [[King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Stakes]] next time under Lester Piggot, confirming that she was superior to her Sandown showing. Nevertheless, Wolver Hollow's win was enough to secure a new career as a stallion.\n\n==Races==\n\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" style=\" text-align:centre; margin-left:1em; float:centre ;border-collapse: collapse; font-size:100%\"\n|-  style=\"background:#dacaa4; text-align:center;\"\n!'''Date'''\n!'''Finish'''\n!'''Race'''\n!'''Dist'''\n!'''Jockey'''\n!'''Winner/Runner up '''\n!'''Track'''\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|06|16}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|New Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|07|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[National_Stakes_(Sandown_Park)|National Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|09|17}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|Imperial Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">6</span>6f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Heath Rose\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|10|14}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Dewhurst Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Dart Board\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|04|22}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Greenham Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Play High\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|05|03}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|[[2000 Guineas Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Doug Smith  (jockey)|Doug Smith ]]\n|[[Royal_Palace_(horse)|Royal Palace]]\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|06|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[St James's Palace Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[George Moore (jockey)|George Moore]]\n|[[Reform (horse)|Reform]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|07|28}}\t\n|5th\n|News of the World Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sucaryl\n|[[Goodwood Racecourse|Goodwood]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|08|28}}\t\n|1st\n|Virginia Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Future Fame\n|[[Newcastle Racecourse|Newcastle]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|07}}\t\n|1st\n|Crathorne Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Scottish Sinbad\n|[[York Racecourse|York]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|16}}\t\n|3rd\n|Wavertree Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Fair Winter\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|10|21}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Lacquer\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|17}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Prix Gontaut-Biron]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Frontal\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|26}}\t\n|1st\n|Prix Ridgway\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Right Honourable\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|9|28}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|World Cup\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|10|19}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Emerilo\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|10}}\t\n|2nd\n|Jubilee Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sovereign Ruler\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|31}}\t\n|6th\n|[[Lockinge Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|[[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]]\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|6|17}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Prince of Wales's Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|7|5}}\t\n|1st\n|[[Eclipse Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Park Top]]\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Stud career==\nWhen owner [[Hope Goddard Iselin]] retired at the age of 102, the horses she still had in training were sent to be sold at Newmarket. The one exception was Wolver Hollow who was given to his former trainer [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On Wolver Hollow's retirement, he was syndicated by the Curragh Bloodstock Agency and initially stood at Athgarvan Stud, The Curragh.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=999}}</ref> Through a friendship between Boyd-Rochfort and Billy Iceton, Wolver Hollow spent his latter breeding career at Tara Stud in County Meath.<ref>Griffiths, Richard. \"Tributes paid after death of renowned stud master Billy Iceton, aged 81.\" Racing Post, May 20, 2010: 17.</ref> Wolver Hollow enjoyed success with his first crop, spearheaded by the classic winning [[Furry Glen]]. His greatest achievement as a stallion came in 1976 when the Henry Cecil trained [[Wollow]] won five top class races, enabling his sire to become the leading sire in the UK and Ireland. Wollow's contribution to this achievement can not be understated. Wolver Hollow earned his accolade with a record of 34 wins from 18 horses amassing \u00a3192,362 in prize money - \u00a3166,389 of which was won by Wollow. Indeed, Wollow's earnings were such that they eclipsed the \u00a3166,323 earned by the progeny of [[Vaguely Noble]], that season's second leading sire.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=825}}</ref> Unsurprisingly, this would represent the zenith of Wolver Hollow's stallion career and while he would produce a further handful of useful horses, none of them would win at the highest level. \n\nAs a damsire, Wolver Hollow could not count any European Group One winners among his descendants although Love A Show was victorious in the 1983 [[Blue Diamond Stakes]]. Other horses of note include Reach, winner of the 1984 [[Royal Lodge Stakes]], Festive Cheer, third in the 1991 [[Phoenix Stakes]], Treasure Hope, winner of the 1992 [[Premio Regina Elena]] (Italian 1000 Guineas), and Wrapping, a runner up in the 1989 [[Oaks d'Italia]]. Wolver Hollow was also the damsire of several useful [[National Hunt]] horses such as Simply Dashing, a high class handicap chaser who finished second in a [[Charlie Hall Chase]], 1992 [[Baring Bingham Novices' Hurdle]] winner Thetford Forest and useful handicapper Latent Talent. \n\nHe was euthanised due to deteriorating health on 13 June 1987.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedigreequery.com/wolver+hollow|title=Wolver Hollow Horse Pedigree|website=www.pedigreequery.com}}</ref>\n\n===Notable progeny===\n\n''c = [[colt (horse)|colt]], f = [[filly]], g = [[gelding]]''\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse\" font-size:80%\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Foaled'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Name'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Dam'''\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Sex'''\n| style=\"width:510px;\"| '''Major Wins and Notable Performances'''\n|-\n| 1971\n| Charlie Bubbles\n| Sixandahalf\n| c\n| 1st [[Hardwicke Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| [[Furry Glen]]\n| Cleftess\n| c\n| 1st [[Marble Hill Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Leopardstown Stakes|Mullion Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Irish 2000 Guineas]] (1974) 1st [[International Stakes (Ireland)|Whitehall Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Vauxhall Trial Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Gallinule Stakes]] (1974) 3rd [[Coventry Stakes]] (1973) 3rd Larkspur Stakes (1973) \n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| Wanlockhead\n| Exultation\n| c\n| 3rd [[Gordon Richards Stakes|Westbury Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| [[Wollow]]\n| Wichuraiana\n| c\n| 1st [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Dewhurst Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Greenham Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[2000 Guineas]] (1976) 1st [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[Sussex Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[International Stakes|Benson & Hedges Gold Cup]] (1976)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| Wolverlife\n| Miralife\n| c\n| 3rd [[Duke of York Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Palace House Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Diamond Jubilee Stakes|Cork and Orrery Stakes]]\n|-\n|-\n| 1975\n| My Hollow\n| Saucy Mine\n| f\n| 1st [[Royal Whip Stakes]] (1980) 1st [[Desmond Stakes]] (1980) 2nd [[Blandford Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Galaxy Libra\n| Garden of Eden\n| c\n| 1st [[Man o' War Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Joe Hirsch Turf Classic Invitational Stakes]] (1981) 3rd [[Charles Whittingham Stakes|Hollywood Invitational Handicap]] (1981) 3rd [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] (1981)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Wolverton\n| Mary Murphy\n| c\n| 1st [[Prix Daniel Wildenstein|Prix du Rond-Point]] (1979) 1st [[Prix Edmond Blanc]] (1980) 2nd [[Prix Greffulhe]] (1979)\n|-\n|-\n| 1977\n| Gift Wrapped\n| Doc Nan\n| f\n| 1st [[Lingfield Oaks Trial]] (1980) 2nd [[Musidora Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Sun Chariot Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Hays\n| Sing A Song\n| c\n| 1st [[Mill Reef Stakes]] (1981) 1st [[2,000 Guineas Trial Stakes]] (1982) 2nd [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Hungerford Stakes]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Teofane\n| The Yellow Girl\n| c\n| 2nd [[Derby Italiano]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1980\n| Sherbaz\n| Shelina\n| c\n| 3rd [[Prix La Rochette]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1981\n| Gamelion\n| Glamingo\n| g\n| 1st Prix des Drags (1986)\n|-\n|-\n| 1983\n| Hollow Hand\n| Fingers\n| c\n| 2nd [[Horris Hill Stakes]] (1985)\n|-\n|}\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Wolver Hollow (GB), bay horse, 1964<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = Sovereign Path (GB)<br />1956\n|m = Cygnet (GB)<br />1950\n|ff = [[Grey Sovereign]] (GB)<br />1948\n|fm = Mountain Path (GB)<br />1948\n|mf = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]] (FR)<br />1942\n|mm = Mrs. Swan Song (IRE)<br />1940\n|fff = [[Nasrullah (horse)|Nasrullah]]\n|ffm = Kong\n|fmf = Bobsleigh\n|fmm = Path Of Peace\n|mff = [[Tourbillon (horse)|Tourbillon]]\n|mfm = Astronomie\n|mmf = Sir Walter Raleigh\n|mmm = Donati's Comet\n|ffff = [[Nearco]]\n|fffm = Mumtaz Begum\n|ffmf = Baytown\n|ffmm = Clang\n|fmff = [[Gainsborough (horse)|Gainsborough]]\n|fmfm = Toboggan\n|fmmf = Winalot\n|fmmm = Grand Peace\n|mfff = [[Ksar (horse)|Ksar]]\n|mffm = Durban\n|mfmf = Asterus\n|mfmm = Likka\n|mmff = Prince Galahad\n|mmfm = Smoke Lass\n|mmmf = Flying Orb\n|mmmm = Sunshot\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKvNyOYoSS0 1969 Eclipse Stakes] (YouTube)\n\n[[Category:1964 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:1987 racehorse deaths]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 19-b]]\n[[Category:British Champion Thoroughbred Sires]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Jair du Cochet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1968: four-year-old season", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolver_Hollow"}
{"title_page": "X-Cutioner's Song", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{About|the Marvel Comics crossover series ''X-Cutioner's Song''|the supervillain|X-Cutioner}}\n{{Infobox comics story arc <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image          = X-Cutioner's Song Cover.jpg\n|imagesize      = <!-- default 250 -->\n|caption        = {{Descript-cvr|X-Cutioner's Song|||1994|type=TPB}}Art by [[Jae Lee]].\n|publisher      = [[Marvel Comics]]\n|startmo        = November\n|startyr        = 1992\n|endmo          = February\n|endyr          = 1993\n|Crossover      = y\n|titles         = ''[[#Stryfe's Strike File|Stryfe's Strike File]] #1''<br><!--\n-->''[[Uncanny X-Men|The Uncanny X-Men]]'' #294-297<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' vol. 1, #84-86<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Men: Legacy|X-Men]]'' vol. 2, #14-16<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Force]]'' vol. 1, #16-19<br /><!--\n-->Cable - Blood and Metal #1-2<br /><!--\n-->What If? #69\n|main_char_team = [[X-Men]]<br/>[[X-Force]]<br/>[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]<br/>[[Mutant Liberation Front]]<br/>[[Stryfe]]\n|writers        = [[Scott Lobdell]], [[Fabian Nicieza]], [[Peter David]]\n|artists        =\n|pencillers     = [[Brandon Peterson]], [[Andy Kubert]], [[Jae Lee]], [[Greg Capullo]]\n|inkers         = [[Terry Austin (comics)|Terry Austin]], [[Mark Pennington (comics)|Mark Pennington]], [[Al Milgrom]], [[Harry Candelario]]\n|letterers      =\n|editors        =\n|colorists      = Mike Thomas, [[Marie Javins]], Glynis Oliver, Joe Rosas, Steve Buccellato\n|TPB            = X-cutioners Song\n|ISBN           = 0-7851-0025-3\n|cat            = X-Men\n|sortkey        = X-Cutioner's Song\n}}\n\"'''X-Cutioner's Song'''\" is a [[fictional crossover|crossover]] storyline published by [[Marvel Comics]]' in twelve parts from November 1992 to early 1993. It ran in ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'', ''[[X-Men: Legacy|X-Men (vol. 2)]]'', ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'', and ''[[X-Force]]'', and featured [[Stryfe]] as the central villain. The story was heavily hyped as revealing the origin of popular ''X-Force'' star [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], but ultimately Cable's origin was not covered in any of the installments.\n\nThe main issues of the crossover were sold polybagged with a special trading card that featured Stryfe's personal views of key characters from the crossover. Because of this, the issues themselves were priced at $1.50, twenty-five cents more than their normal price of $1.25.\n\n==Plot==\nMutant pop-star [[Lila Cheney]] organizes a free concert in [[Central Park]] to promote diversity in society and invites [[Professor X|Professor Charles Xavier]] to speak at the concert. His speech is interrupted by [[Stryfe]] who, disguised as his doppelganger and nemesis [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], shoots Xavier with a bullet that infects the professor with a lethal strain of the [[Techno-organic virus]].\n\nMeanwhile, [[War (Marvel Comics character)#Abraham Kieros|War]] and [[Famine (comics)|Famine]], the [[Horsemen of Apocalypse]], attack [[Iceman (comics)|Iceman]] and [[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]], distracting them from [[Caliban (comics)|Caliban]], who kidnaps [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] and [[Jean Grey]]. The Horsemen are working for [[Mr. Sinister]], who is impersonating the Horsemen's former master [[Apocalypse (comics)|Apocalypse]]. Mr. Sinister organized the kidnapping as part of his newly formed alliance with Stryfe. Stryfe trades Mr. Sinister a canister containing the past and future Summers family DNA history, and receives Jean Grey and Cyclops in the exchange.\n\nWhile Xavier is rushed to the hospital, X-Factor and the Blue X-Men strike team go after [[X-Force]], Cable's team of mutants. X-Force, however, is in the dark about Cable's current location (having been separated from him during a [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]-organized raid of their headquarters). But mutual distrust causes the two groups to attack and ultimately capture X-Force. Meanwhile, Mr. Sinister doublecrosses Stryfe by revealing to the X-Men that Stryfe, under the guise of Cable, was the shooter.\n\nWhile the Blue X-Men strike team, X-Factor, [[Tabitha Smith|Boom Boom]] and [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]] go after the [[Mutant Liberation Front]], [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]]'s Gold X-Men strike team, along with [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], confront Apocalypse over Scott and Jean's kidnapping, hoping as well to gain a cure for the virus that is threatening Xavier's life. Apocalypse is incredibly weak, having been nearly killed by Cyclops in their previous encounter and prematurely awoken from his regeneration chamber by his minions the [[Dark Riders (comics)|Dark Riders]]. After learning from the Dark Riders that someone had been impersonating him, and ordered his old minions to kidnap Jean and Scott, Apocalypse barely escapes with his life. [[Archangel (comics)|Archangel]] finds himself becoming more and more consumed with punishing Apocalypse for his crimes, most notably Apocalypse's converting Archangel into the blue-skinned, metal winged angel of death.\n\nThe Mutant Liberation Front is defeated, though at the cost of [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] being blinded by MLF member [[Strobe (comics)|Strobe]]. Meanwhile, [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]] and [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] locate Cable and after a brawl, decide to give him the benefit of the doubt and work together to find Jean and Scott.\n\nApocalypse is ambushed by [[Stryfe]], who declares that he is out for revenge for unknown wrongs committed against him as a child by Apocalypse. After Stryfe stabs him in the chest, Apocalypse escapes and seeks refuge amongst the X-Men, ultimately curing Xavier of the [[techno-organic virus]] as payment for [[sanctuary]].\n\nCyclops and Jean are systematically tortured by Stryfe, who blames the two mutants for ruining his life, a claim that leaves the two X-Men stunned since they never encountered Stryfe before their kidnapping. Stryfe and his new minions the Dark Riders, who pledge their allegiance to Stryfe after he defeats Apocalypse, move the two to Apocalypse's former base on the Moon. Scott and Jean escape, entering the vacuum before realizing they are not on Earth. Her powers no longer blocked, Jean sends a frantic SOS to Wolverine.\n\nThe X-Men, knowing Xavier will live now that Apocalypse has purged the techno-virus from him, head into space to save their teammates. Cable, Wolverine, and Bishop head out to Stryfe's base on the Moon too and arrive there first, decimating Stryfe's defenses just as the X-Men ([[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]], [[Psylocke]], [[Polaris (Marvel Comics)|Polaris]], Cannonball, [[Havok (comics)|Havok]], Iceman and Archangel) and Apocalypse arrive. Splitting up, Apocalypse is ambushed by the [[Dark Riders (comics)|Dark Riders]], who beat their former master to the brink of death. Apocalypse is later confronted by Archangel who refuses Apocalypse's request for a mercy killing.\n\nUpon catching Jean and Scott Summers outside the moonbase, Stryfe takes them to a giant time portal he had constructed on the Moon. As [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], Cannonball, Havok and Polaris make their way to the tower, a forcefield is activated that prevents any without the Summers DNA from approaching the tower just as Stryfe activated the tower's time portal technology. Stryfe planned this so he could confront Cable alone, and though Havok has enough genetic similarity to Scott to pass through the forcefield, doing so renders him unconscious. Cable finds himself hopelessly outmatched by Stryfe, but as they battle, Jean Grey and Cyclops break free and Havok regains consciousness. Driven to despair, Stryfe tries to collapse the active tower upon the X-Men. Cable grabs Stryfe and orders Cyclops to activate the time vortex, a plan that would kill both Stryfe and Cable. Cyclops reluctantly does so; both men are sucked into a massive vortex that is created as the tower explodes. Cyclops and Jean Grey begin to suspect that either Stryfe or Cable is Cyclops' son Nathan Christopher Summers, who Cyclops was forced to abandon and send into the future after Apocalypse infected him with a techno-virus.\n\n[[Mr. Sinister]] has a minion, Gordan, open the canister given to him by Stryfe, only to find it apparently empty. Though not revealed in ''X-Cutioner's Song'', the canister in fact contained the [[Legacy Virus]].\n\nOf note, in X-men issue #303 Illyana Rasputina the sister of colossus died of the Legacy virus promoting him to eventually leave the X-men and join Magento for a time\n===Epilogue===\nProfessor X discovers that the techno-organic virus has left him temporarily capable of walking and spends his few hours without paralysis bonding with [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]]. [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] and [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] hang out together as Rogue agrees to let Gambit be her \"eyes\" until she regains her sight, laying the groundwork for the two finally becoming a couple. Archangel and [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] rebuild the bar that Cyclops and Jean Grey were kidnapped in and think back to their days as the original X-Men.\n\n==''Stryfe's Strike File''==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Stryfesf.jpg|Cover to ''Stryfe's Strike File'' #1. Art by Andy Kubert.|thumb|200px]] -->\n''Stryfe's Strike File'' was the name of a 1993 ''[[X-Men]]'' one-shot written by [[Fabian Nicieza]] and [[Scott Lobdell]]. It included several years worth of foreshadowing of Lobdell and Nicieza's X-Men plotlines, most notably the Legacy Virus plotline. The comic framing device was that the files in the one-shot were on a CD-ROM found at Stryfe's base by Bishop and handed over to Xavier without telling anyone else about it. After nearly two dozen pages of text and picture files, most of which were taken from the trading card inserts included in the individual issues of the crossover, the book ended with a closing sequence where Xavier destroys the disk rather than showing it to Cyclops and Jean Grey.\n\nThe book contained entries for [[Graydon Creed]], [[Threnody (comics)|Threnody]], and [[Holocaust (Marvel Comics)|Holocaust]] prior to their first appearances elsewhere. Graydon Creed would appear as a villain two months later, Threnody would appear eleven months later, yet Holocaust would not appear in the [[X-Men]] comics until the alternate reality ''[[Age of Apocalypse]]'' storyline. The version found in that storyline differs from the one found in Stryfe's Strike File in that the Age of Apocalypse Holocaust requires a containment suit and is very talkative while the Holocaust in the files does not need a containment suit and is a silent killer.\n\n==Publication==\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #294\n#''X-Factor'' #84\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #14\n#''X-Force'' #16\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #295\n#''X-Factor'' #85\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #15\n#''X-Force'' #17\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #296\n#''X-Factor'' #86\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #16\n#''X-Force'' #18\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #297 (Epilogue)\n#''X-Force'' #19 (Epilogue)\n# \"Stryfe's Strike File\"\n\n===Collected editions===\nThe storyline (except for \"Epilogues 1 & 2 \" & \"Stryfe's Strike File\") have been collected into a [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]]:\n\n*''X-Men: X-Cutioners Song'' (May 1994, {{ISBN|0-7851-0025-3}})\n\nIt has also been collected into a hardcover:\n\n*''X-Men: X-Cutioners Song'' (368 pages, October 19, 2011, {{ISBN|0785156100}}) \nCollects Uncanny X-Men #294-297, X-Factor #84-86, X-Men #14-16, X-Force #16-19 and Stryfe's Strike File\n\n==Publication history==\nIn 1991, the X-Men franchise had reached a popularity level unheard of at the time, with the release of the high selling ''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #1 and ''X-Force'' #1, as well as the contributions of popular artists [[Jim Lee]], [[Rob Liefeld]] and [[Whilce Portacio]] to the main X-Men books. But by 1992, Portacio, Lee and Liefeld left Marvel Comics to form their own comic company [[Image Comics]], alongside several other high profile Marvel artists. New writers and artists were quickly drafted to replace the departing fan favorite artists, most notably writers [[Scott Lobdell]] and [[Fabian Nicieza]] and artist [[Greg Capullo]].\n\nAt a writer's retreat held by the X-Men writing staff in 1992, the writers began to plan which direction for the X-Men. A massive crossover had been decided upon prior to the formation of Image Comics and it was decided by the new writers to continue with the plan as a means to keep attention on the X-Men books at the time. The subject of the crossover was having the X-Men face their biggest enemies at the time, Stryfe, Apocalypse, and Mr. Sinister, and revealing the origin of the popular X-Force leader Cable.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nA year earlier it was heavily implied that Cable was Nathan Christopher Summers, the infant son of X-Man Cyclops and Madelyne Prior.<ref>[[Simonson, Louise]] (w). ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' #65-68. [[Marvel Comics]]</ref> Meanwhile, Stryfe revealed that he had the same face as Cable.<ref>[[Liefeld, Rob]]; [[Nicieza, Fabian]] (w), Liefeld, Rob (a). ''[[New Mutants]]'' #100. Marvel Comics</ref> As fans had picked up on these plot threads, Fabian Nicieza pushed for the reveal that Stryfe was the time-displaced Nathan Summers and that Cable was the heroic clone of the missing Summers child.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nDuring the planning of the crossover, Scott Lobdell and Fabian Nicieza wanted to feature the return of Magneto, believed to be dead at the time, during the storyline, mainly to provide fans with an added shock moment and to add to the impact of the story, which would have the X-Men and their allies face down against their worst enemies in a single crisis.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} [[Peter David]] sarcastically proclaimed that Magneto should remove Wolverine's [[adamantium]] skeleton upon his return. While the plan to make Magneto's return was dropped from the storyline, David's suggestion would be used when the writers brought Magneto back the following year as part of the \"[[Fatal Attractions (comics)|Fatal Attractions]]\" storyline.<ref>Cronin, Brian (March 29, 2007). [http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/03/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-96/ \"Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #96\"]. [[Comic Book Resources]].</ref><ref>[[David, Peter]] (June 23, 2006). ''Writing for Comics with Peter David'', Impact</ref>\n\nThere is a long-standing rumor that X-Men editor Bob Harras forced Lobdell and Nicieza to change the ending of the story to remove what was supposed to be the main drawing point of the storyline: Cable's origin. However, Nicieza has stated that this was not the case.<ref>Cronin, Brian (April 5, 2007). [http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/04/05/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-97/ \"Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #97\"]. Comic Book Resources.</ref> The full details of the origin Cable (and Stryfe) would be held back until 1994, when it was revealed that Cable was in truth Nathan Christopher Summers and that Stryfe, not Cable, was the clone.<ref name=\"Cable6\">''Cable'' #6-8. Marvel Comics</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSales of ''X-Cutioner's Song'' were considerably higher than the issues of the participating series which preceded and succeeded it. However, the story was considered a disappointment by fans, chiefly because it had been promised that it would reveal Cable's origin, but instead provided only cryptic and sometimes confusing hints about the identities of Cable and Stryfe.<ref name=\"futureNow\">{{cite news | last = O'Neill | first= Patrick Daniel | date = August 1993 | title = The Future is Now | work = [[Wizard (magazine)|Wizard]]: X-Men Turn Thirty | issue = | pages = 12\u201325}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nStryfe and Apocalypse were both brought back to life. Excluding the \"Age of Apocalypse\" storyline, Apocalypse would return in ''Cable'' #19, while Stryfe would return as a ghost who possessed Cable. The story ended with Cable freeing himself from Stryfe's control, sending Stryfe's spirit to Hell for all eternity.<ref name=\"Cable6\"/> Stryfe reappeared when his ghost attempted to escape Hell by possessing X-Force member Warpath but was foiled by the members of X-Force.<ref>''X-Force'' #74. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nUltimately Stryfe would be brought back to life as a time anomaly, having shown up out of the blue alongside the Dark Riders during a crossover between Cable and [[X-Man]] and would go on to bedevil the X-Men until his most death during the Gambit/Bishop mini-series.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Stryfe would yet again return after the \"[[Decimation (comics)|Decimation]]\" storyline and appeared to perish again, although it is unknown if it is a Stryfe from another reality.\n\nThe major long-term result of \"X-Cutioner's Song\" was the [[Legacy Virus]]. Stryfe had earlier given [[Mister Sinister]] a canister that he claimed contained two thousand years worth of genetic material from the Summers bloodline. When Sinister opened it after Stryfe was apparently killed by Cable, he found nothing inside. The canister actually contained a plague, Stryfe's \"Legacy\" to the world. The virus, presumably from the future, was 100% fatal and struck only mutants but later infected the human doctor and long-time X-Men ally, [[Moira MacTaggert]]. MacTaggert would ultimately develop a cure just before her death, though it would cost the mutant Peter Rasputin ([[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]]) his life, due to the cure requiring a mutant to die in order to activate it.\n\n==In other media==\nThe 1995 video game ''[[X-Men: Gamesmaster's Legacy]]'' is loosely based on the events of \"X-Cutioner's Song\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Executioner's Song]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060717234705/http://www.mutanthigh.com/xcutionerssong.html X-Cutioners Song X-Over issue-by-issue synopsis]\n*{{comicbookdb|type=storyarc|id=125|title=X-Cutioner's Song}}\n\n{{X-Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Comics by Fabian Nicieza]]\n[[Category:Comics by Peter David]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{About|the Marvel Comics crossover series ''X-Cutioner's Song''|the supervillain|X-Cutioner}}\n{{Infobox comics story arc <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|title          = X-Cutioner's Song\n|image          = X-Cutioner's Song Cover.jpg\n|imagesize      = <!-- default 250 -->\n|caption        = {{Descript-cvr|X-Cutioner's Song|||1994|type=TPB}}Art by [[Jae Lee]].\n|publisher      = [[Marvel Comics]]\n|startmo        = November\n|startyr        = 1992\n|endmo          = February\n|endyr          = 1993\n|Crossover      = y\n|titles         = ''[[#Stryfe's Strike File|Stryfe's Strike File]] #1''<br><!--\n-->''[[Uncanny X-Men|The Uncanny X-Men]]'' #294-297<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' vol. 1, #84-86<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Men: Legacy|X-Men]]'' vol. 2, #14-16<br /><!--\n-->''[[X-Force]]'' vol. 1, #16-19<br /><!--\n-->Cable - Blood and Metal #1-2<br /><!--\n-->What If? #69\n|main_char_team = [[X-Men]]<br/>[[X-Force]]<br/>[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]<br/>[[Mutant Liberation Front]]<br/>[[Stryfe]]\n|writers        = [[Scott Lobdell]], [[Fabian Nicieza]], [[Peter David]]\n|artists        =\n|pencillers     = [[Brandon Peterson]], [[Andy Kubert]], [[Jae Lee]], [[Greg Capullo]]\n|inkers         = [[Terry Austin (comics)|Terry Austin]], [[Mark Pennington (comics)|Mark Pennington]], [[Al Milgrom]], [[Harry Candelario]]\n|letterers      =\n|editors        =\n|colorists      = Mike Thomas, [[Marie Javins]], Glynis Oliver, Joe Rosas, Steve Buccellato\n|TPB            = X-cutioners Song\n|ISBN           = 0-7851-0025-3\n|cat            = X-Men\n|sortkey        = X-Cutioner's Song\n}}\n\"'''X-Cutioner's Song'''\" is a [[fictional crossover|crossover]] storyline published by [[Marvel Comics]]' in twelve parts from November 1992 to early 1993. It ran in ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'', ''[[X-Men: Legacy|X-Men (vol. 2)]]'', ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'', and ''[[X-Force]]'', and featured [[Stryfe]] as the central villain. The story was heavily hyped as revealing the origin of popular ''X-Force'' star [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], but ultimately Cable's origin was not covered in any of the installments.\n\nThe main issues of the crossover were sold polybagged with a special trading card that featured Stryfe's personal views of key characters from the crossover. Because of this, the issues themselves were priced at $1.50, twenty-five cents more than their normal price of $1.25.\n\n==Plot==\nMutant pop-star [[Lila Cheney]] organizes a free concert in [[Central Park]] to promote diversity in society and invites [[Professor X|Professor Charles Xavier]] to speak at the concert. His speech is interrupted by [[Stryfe]] who, disguised as his doppelganger and nemesis [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], shoots Xavier with a bullet that infects the professor with a lethal strain of the [[Techno-organic virus]].\n\nMeanwhile, [[War (Marvel Comics character)#Abraham Kieros|War]] and [[Famine (comics)|Famine]], the [[Horsemen of Apocalypse]], attack [[Iceman (comics)|Iceman]] and [[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]], distracting them from [[Caliban (comics)|Caliban]], who kidnaps [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] and [[Jean Grey]]. The Horsemen are working for [[Mr. Sinister]], who is impersonating the Horsemen's former master [[Apocalypse (comics)|Apocalypse]]. Mr. Sinister organized the kidnapping as part of his newly formed alliance with Stryfe. Stryfe trades Mr. Sinister a canister containing the past and future Summers family DNA history, and receives Jean Grey and Cyclops in the exchange.\n\nWhile Xavier is rushed to the hospital, X-Factor and the Blue X-Men strike team go after [[X-Force]], Cable's team of mutants. X-Force, however, is in the dark about Cable's current location (having been separated from him during a [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]-organized raid of their headquarters). But mutual distrust causes the two groups to attack and ultimately capture X-Force. Meanwhile, Mr. Sinister doublecrosses Stryfe by revealing to the X-Men that Stryfe, under the guise of Cable, was the shooter.\n\nWhile the Blue X-Men strike team, X-Factor, [[Tabitha Smith|Boom Boom]] and [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]] go after the [[Mutant Liberation Front]], [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]]'s Gold X-Men strike team, along with [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]], confront Apocalypse over Scott and Jean's kidnapping, hoping as well to gain a cure for the virus that is threatening Xavier's life. Apocalypse is incredibly weak, having been nearly killed by Cyclops in their previous encounter and prematurely awoken from his regeneration chamber by his minions the [[Dark Riders (comics)|Dark Riders]]. After learning from the Dark Riders that someone had been impersonating him, and ordered his old minions to kidnap Jean and Scott, Apocalypse barely escapes with his life. [[Archangel (comics)|Archangel]] finds himself becoming more and more consumed with punishing Apocalypse for his crimes, most notably Apocalypse's converting Archangel into the blue-skinned, metal winged angel of death.\n\nThe Mutant Liberation Front is defeated, though at the cost of [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] being blinded by MLF member [[Strobe (comics)|Strobe]]. Meanwhile, [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]] and [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] locate Cable and after a brawl, decide to give him the benefit of the doubt and work together to find Jean and Scott.\n\nApocalypse is ambushed by [[Stryfe]], who declares that he is out for revenge for unknown wrongs committed against him as a child by Apocalypse. After Stryfe stabs him in the chest, Apocalypse escapes and seeks refuge amongst the X-Men, ultimately curing Xavier of the [[techno-organic virus]] as payment for [[sanctuary]].\n\nCyclops and Jean are systematically tortured by Stryfe, who blames the two mutants for ruining his life, a claim that leaves the two X-Men stunned since they never encountered Stryfe before their kidnapping. Stryfe and his new minions the Dark Riders, who pledge their allegiance to Stryfe after he defeats Apocalypse, move the two to Apocalypse's former base on the Moon. Scott and Jean escape, entering the vacuum before realizing they are not on Earth. Her powers no longer blocked, Jean sends a frantic SOS to Wolverine.\n\nThe X-Men, knowing Xavier will live now that Apocalypse has purged the techno-virus from him, head into space to save their teammates. Cable, Wolverine, and Bishop head out to Stryfe's base on the Moon too and arrive there first, decimating Stryfe's defenses just as the X-Men ([[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]], [[Psylocke]], [[Polaris (Marvel Comics)|Polaris]], Cannonball, [[Havok (comics)|Havok]], Iceman and Archangel) and Apocalypse arrive. Splitting up, Apocalypse is ambushed by the [[Dark Riders (comics)|Dark Riders]], who beat their former master to the brink of death. Apocalypse is later confronted by Archangel who refuses Apocalypse's request for a mercy killing.\n\nUpon catching Jean and Scott Summers outside the moonbase, Stryfe takes them to a giant time portal he had constructed on the Moon. As [[Cable (comics)|Cable]], Cannonball, Havok and Polaris make their way to the tower, a forcefield is activated that prevents any without the Summers DNA from approaching the tower just as Stryfe activated the tower's time portal technology. Stryfe planned this so he could confront Cable alone, and though Havok has enough genetic similarity to Scott to pass through the forcefield, doing so renders him unconscious. Cable finds himself hopelessly outmatched by Stryfe, but as they battle, Jean Grey and Cyclops break free and Havok regains consciousness. Driven to despair, Stryfe tries to collapse the active tower upon the X-Men. Cable grabs Stryfe and orders Cyclops to activate the time vortex, a plan that would kill both Stryfe and Cable. Cyclops reluctantly does so; both men are sucked into a massive vortex that is created as the tower explodes. Cyclops and Jean Grey begin to suspect that either Stryfe or Cable is Cyclops' son Nathan Christopher Summers, who Cyclops was forced to abandon and send into the future after Apocalypse infected him with a techno-virus.\n\n[[Mr. Sinister]] has a minion, Gordan, open the canister given to him by Stryfe, only to find it apparently empty. Though not revealed in ''X-Cutioner's Song'', the canister in fact contained the [[Legacy Virus]].\n\nOf note, in X-men issue #303 Illyana Rasputina the sister of colossus died of the Legacy virus promoting him to eventually leave the X-men and join Magento for a time\n===Epilogue===\nProfessor X discovers that the techno-organic virus has left him temporarily capable of walking and spends his few hours without paralysis bonding with [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]]. [[Rogue (comics)|Rogue]] and [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] hang out together as Rogue agrees to let Gambit be her \"eyes\" until she regains her sight, laying the groundwork for the two finally becoming a couple. Archangel and [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] rebuild the bar that Cyclops and Jean Grey were kidnapped in and think back to their days as the original X-Men.\n\n==''Stryfe's Strike File''==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Stryfesf.jpg|Cover to ''Stryfe's Strike File'' #1. Art by Andy Kubert.|thumb|200px]] -->\n''Stryfe's Strike File'' was the name of a 1993 ''[[X-Men]]'' one-shot written by [[Fabian Nicieza]] and [[Scott Lobdell]]. It included several years worth of foreshadowing of Lobdell and Nicieza's X-Men plotlines, most notably the Legacy Virus plotline. The comic framing device was that the files in the one-shot were on a CD-ROM found at Stryfe's base by Bishop and handed over to Xavier without telling anyone else about it. After nearly two dozen pages of text and picture files, most of which were taken from the trading card inserts included in the individual issues of the crossover, the book ended with a closing sequence where Xavier destroys the disk rather than showing it to Cyclops and Jean Grey.\n\nThe book contained entries for [[Graydon Creed]], [[Threnody (comics)|Threnody]], and [[Holocaust (Marvel Comics)|Holocaust]] prior to their first appearances elsewhere. Graydon Creed would appear as a villain two months later, Threnody would appear eleven months later, yet Holocaust would not appear in the [[X-Men]] comics until the alternate reality ''[[Age of Apocalypse]]'' storyline. The version found in that storyline differs from the one found in Stryfe's Strike File in that the Age of Apocalypse Holocaust requires a containment suit and is very talkative while the Holocaust in the files does not need a containment suit and is a silent killer.\n\n==Publication==\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #294\n#''X-Factor'' #84\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #14\n#''X-Force'' #16\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #295\n#''X-Factor'' #85\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #15\n#''X-Force'' #17\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #296\n#''X-Factor'' #86\n#''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #16\n#''X-Force'' #18\n#''Uncanny X-Men'' #297 (Epilogue)\n#''X-Force'' #19 (Epilogue)\n# \"Stryfe's Strike File\"\n\n===Collected editions===\nThe storyline (except for \"Epilogues 1 & 2 \" & \"Stryfe's Strike File\") have been collected into a [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]]:\n\n*''X-Men: X-Cutioners Song'' (May 1994, {{ISBN|0-7851-0025-3}})\n\nIt has also been collected into a hardcover:\n\n*''X-Men: X-Cutioners Song'' (368 pages, October 19, 2011, {{ISBN|0785156100}}) \nCollects Uncanny X-Men #294-297, X-Factor #84-86, X-Men #14-16, X-Force #16-19 and Stryfe's Strike File\n\n==Publication history==\nIn 1991, the X-Men franchise had reached a popularity level unheard of at the time, with the release of the high selling ''X-Men'' (vol. 2) #1 and ''X-Force'' #1, as well as the contributions of popular artists [[Jim Lee]], [[Rob Liefeld]] and [[Whilce Portacio]] to the main X-Men books. But by 1992, Portacio, Lee and Liefeld left Marvel Comics to form their own comic company [[Image Comics]], alongside several other high profile Marvel artists. New writers and artists were quickly drafted to replace the departing fan favorite artists, most notably writers [[Scott Lobdell]] and [[Fabian Nicieza]] and artist [[Greg Capullo]].\n\nAt a writer's retreat held by the X-Men writing staff in 1992, the writers began to plan which direction for the X-Men. A massive crossover had been decided upon prior to the formation of Image Comics and it was decided by the new writers to continue with the plan as a means to keep attention on the X-Men books at the time. The subject of the crossover was having the X-Men face their biggest enemies at the time, Stryfe, Apocalypse, and Mr. Sinister, and revealing the origin of the popular X-Force leader Cable.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nA year earlier it was heavily implied that Cable was Nathan Christopher Summers, the infant son of X-Man Cyclops and Madelyne Prior.<ref>[[Simonson, Louise]] (w). ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' #65-68. [[Marvel Comics]]</ref> Meanwhile, Stryfe revealed that he had the same face as Cable.<ref>[[Liefeld, Rob]]; [[Nicieza, Fabian]] (w), Liefeld, Rob (a). ''[[New Mutants]]'' #100. Marvel Comics</ref> As fans had picked up on these plot threads, Fabian Nicieza pushed for the reveal that Stryfe was the time-displaced Nathan Summers and that Cable was the heroic clone of the missing Summers child.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nDuring the planning of the crossover, Scott Lobdell and Fabian Nicieza wanted to feature the return of Magneto, believed to be dead at the time, during the storyline, mainly to provide fans with an added shock moment and to add to the impact of the story, which would have the X-Men and their allies face down against their worst enemies in a single crisis.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} [[Peter David]] sarcastically proclaimed that Magneto should remove Wolverine's [[adamantium]] skeleton upon his return. While the plan to make Magneto's return was dropped from the storyline, David's suggestion would be used when the writers brought Magneto back the following year as part of the \"[[Fatal Attractions (comics)|Fatal Attractions]]\" storyline.<ref>Cronin, Brian (March 29, 2007). [http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/03/29/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-96/ \"Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #96\"]. [[Comic Book Resources]].</ref><ref>[[David, Peter]] (June 23, 2006). ''Writing for Comics with Peter David'', Impact</ref>\n\nThere is a long-standing rumor that X-Men editor Bob Harras forced Lobdell and Nicieza to change the ending of the story to remove what was supposed to be the main drawing point of the storyline: Cable's origin. However, Nicieza has stated that this was not the case.<ref>Cronin, Brian (April 5, 2007). [http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2007/04/05/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-97/ \"Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #97\"]. Comic Book Resources.</ref> The full details of the origin Cable (and Stryfe) would be held back until 1994, when it was revealed that Cable was in truth Nathan Christopher Summers and that Stryfe, not Cable, was the clone.<ref name=\"Cable6\">''Cable'' #6-8. Marvel Comics</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSales of ''X-Cutioner's Song'' were considerably higher than the issues of the participating series which preceded and succeeded it. However, the story was considered a disappointment by fans, chiefly because it had been promised that it would reveal Cable's origin, but instead provided only cryptic and sometimes confusing hints about the identities of Cable and Stryfe.<ref name=\"futureNow\">{{cite news | last = O'Neill | first= Patrick Daniel | date = August 1993 | title = The Future is Now | work = [[Wizard (magazine)|Wizard]]: X-Men Turn Thirty | issue = | pages = 12\u201325}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nStryfe and Apocalypse were both brought back to life. Excluding the \"Age of Apocalypse\" storyline, Apocalypse would return in ''Cable'' #19, while Stryfe would return as a ghost who possessed Cable. The story ended with Cable freeing himself from Stryfe's control, sending Stryfe's spirit to Hell for all eternity.<ref name=\"Cable6\"/> Stryfe reappeared when his ghost attempted to escape Hell by possessing X-Force member Warpath but was foiled by the members of X-Force.<ref>''X-Force'' #74. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nUltimately Stryfe would be brought back to life as a time anomaly, having shown up out of the blue alongside the Dark Riders during a crossover between Cable and [[X-Man]] and would go on to bedevil the X-Men until his most death during the Gambit/Bishop mini-series.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Stryfe would yet again return after the \"[[Decimation (comics)|Decimation]]\" storyline and appeared to perish again, although it is unknown if it is a Stryfe from another reality.\n\nThe major long-term result of \"X-Cutioner's Song\" was the [[Legacy Virus]]. Stryfe had earlier given [[Mister Sinister]] a canister that he claimed contained two thousand years worth of genetic material from the Summers bloodline. When Sinister opened it after Stryfe was apparently killed by Cable, he found nothing inside. The canister actually contained a plague, Stryfe's \"Legacy\" to the world. The virus, presumably from the future, was 100% fatal and struck only mutants but later infected the human doctor and long-time X-Men ally, [[Moira MacTaggert]]. MacTaggert would ultimately develop a cure just before her death, though it would cost the mutant Peter Rasputin ([[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]]) his life, due to the cure requiring a mutant to die in order to activate it.\n\n==In other media==\nThe 1995 video game ''[[X-Men: Gamesmaster's Legacy]]'' is loosely based on the events of \"X-Cutioner's Song\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Executioner's Song]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060717234705/http://www.mutanthigh.com/xcutionerssong.html X-Cutioners Song X-Over issue-by-issue synopsis]\n*{{comicbookdb|type=storyarc|id=125|title=X-Cutioner's Song}}\n\n{{X-Comics}}\n\n[[Category:Comics by Fabian Nicieza]]\n[[Category:Comics by Peter David]]\n", "name_user": "TheSandDoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "rm redundant title param", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-Cutioner%27s_Song"}
{"title_page": "Louise Haigh", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Louise Haigh\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Louise Haigh MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| status = Interim\n| leader = [[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start = 6 April 2020\n| term_end  = \n| predecessor = [[Tony Lloyd]] <small>(on medical leave}</small>\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Policing]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 3 July 2017\n| term_end1 = 6 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Lyn Brown (politician)|Lyn Brown]]\n| successor1 = [[Sarah Jones (politician)|Sarah Jones]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Digital Economy]]\n| leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 10 October 2016\n| term_end2 = 3 July 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Chi Onwurah]]\n| successor2 = [[Liam Byrne]]\n| office3 = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Civil Service and Digital Reform]]\n| leader3 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3 = 18 September 2015\n| term_end3 = 10 October 2016\n| predecessor3 = ''Office established''\n| successor3 = [[Steve Reed (politician)|Steve Reed]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]]\n| term_start4 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = [[Meg Munn]]\n| successor4 = \n| majority4 = 8,520 (20.0%)\n| birth_name = Louise Margaret Haigh\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|7|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Sheffield]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| website = {{url|louisehaigh.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Louise Margaret Haigh''' (born 22 July 1987) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician. She was elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]] at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], as the youngest Labour member of that parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000923 |title=Sheffield Heeley Parliamentary constituency |work=Election 2015 |publisher=BBC News |year=2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHaigh grew up on [[Abbeydale Road]], [[Sheffield]], and now lives in [[Norfolk Park]], Sheffield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/about_louise|title=About Louise|year=2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> She was educated at [[Sheffield High School, South Yorkshire|Sheffield High School]], an [[independent school]].<ref name=star-20140813>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/sheffield-heeley-candidate-could-be-youngest-mp-1-6781098 |title=Sheffield Heeley candidate could be youngest MP |first=Ellen |last=Beardmore |newspaper=The Star |location=Sheffield |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> She then studied Government and Economics at the [[London School of Economics]] but did not complete the course, and opted to study politics at the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sheffieldhighschool.org.uk/why-us/alumnae/the-alumnae-network/louise-haigh-mp/|title=Louise Haigh MP \u2013 Sheffield Girls School|website=Sheffield Girls High School}}</ref> Her grandfather and uncle were trade union officials.<ref name=\"Politics\">{{cite web |url=http://politics.co.uk/reference/louise-haigh |title=Louise Haigh |publisher= Politics.co.uk |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Haigh worked for the local council youth service between 2006 and 2008. She then began working in Parliament, where she was the co-ordinator of the All Party Parliamentary Group on International Corporate Responsibility.<ref name=\"Politics\"/> During this time, she was also a [[Unite the Union|Unite]] shop steward and volunteered as a [[Special Constable]] in the [[Metropolitan Special Constabulary]] between 2009 and 2011.<ref name=\"Profiles: Louise Haigh\">{{cite web|url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/20899/|title=Profiles: Louise Haigh|year=2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012, Haigh worked for [[Aviva]] as Public Policy Manager, responsible for corporate governance and responsible investment policy.<ref name=\"Profiles: Louise Haigh\"/><ref name=labour-cv>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/people/detail/louise-haigh |title=Louise Haigh |publisher=Labour Party |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asx.com.au/documents/public-consultations/aviva-plc-submission-15Nov13.pdf |title=Towards an agreement on corporate sustainability reporting |publisher=Aviva Investors |year=2013 |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHaigh was selected to stand for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]] in May 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/time-is-right-for-sheffield-mp-to-stand-down-1-6612067 |title='Time is right' for Sheffield MP to stand down |first=Ellen |last=Beardmore |newspaper=The Star| location=Sheffield |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> and was elected to Parliament at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|May 2015 general election]].\n\nHaigh was one of 36 Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election of 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election |work=The New Statesman |date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Haigh was appointed Shadow Minister for Civil Service and Digital Reform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/pages/labours-foi-review |title=Labour's FOI Review |publisher=Labour Party |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-mp-louise-haigh-labour-digital-brief |title=Jeremy Corbyn appoints MP Louise Haigh to Labour digital brief |first=Colin |last=Marrs |newspaper=Civil Service World |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> The role, newly expanded under Jeremy Corbyn,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukauthority.com/news/5629/louise-haigh-takes-labour-digital-role|title=Louise Haigh takes Labour digital role |first=Mark |last=Say |publisher=UK Authority.com |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> covers the Government's digital strategy, the [[Freedom of Information Act 2000|Freedom of Information Act]], data security and privacy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/sheffield-mp-louise-haigh-joins-shadow-cabinet-1-7469818 |title=Sheffield MP Louise Haigh joins Shadow Cabinet |first=Lauren |last=Clarke |newspaper=The Star |location=Sheffield |date=18 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> In this role, Haigh was critical of a 2016 reshuffle of Permanent Secretaries which saw two fewer women as departmental heads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/interview/louise-haigh-interview-shadow-cabinet-office-minister-jeremy-corbyn-whitehall |title=Louise Haigh interview: the shadow Cabinet Office minister on Jeremy Corbyn, Whitehall diversity \u2013 and why the Tories have \"always understood\" civil service reform {{!}} Civil Service World |website=www.civilserviceworld.com |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> She opposed the closure of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills office in Sheffield city centre, saying the decision demonstrated \"contempt\" for the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/bis-sheffield-closure-confirmed-%E2%80%93-full-details-and-reaction-staff-unions-and-mps |title=BIS Sheffield closure confirmed \u2013 full details and reaction from staff, unions and MPs {{!}} Civil Service World |website=www.civilserviceworld.com |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2016, she was made Shadow Minister for the Digital Economy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/shadow_minister_digital_economy |title=Louise appointed Shadow Minister for the Digital Economy \u2013 Louise Haigh, Labour Member of Parliament for Sheffield Heeley |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> Haigh served in this role during the passage of the [[Digital Economy Act 2017|Digital Economy Act (2017)]] and introduced a number of amendments, including an obligation for television broadcasters to include subtitles and closed captioning in on-demand content online which was adopted by a subsequent Government amendment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cable.co.uk/news/digital-economy-bill-will-require-on-demand-programmes-to-include-subtitles-700001735/ |title=Digital Economy Bill will require on-demand programmes to include subtitles |website=www.cable.co.uk |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> She has repeatedly raised concerns about child protection online, including calling for social media companies to recognise \"that alongside their new-found power, they have responsibilities\" in dealing with harmful and illegal content.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/it-is-time-to-make-the-internet-giants-meet-their-responsibility-grfghjx6h |title=It is time to make the internet giants meet their responsibility |last=Haigh |first=Louise |accessdate=22 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nShe also called for compulsory online education alongside sex and relationships education in schools, citing an 800% increase in children contacting the [[NSPCC]] about online abuse.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/louise-haigh-mp/sex-education_b_13126998.html?1479741341& |title=Why Our 'Smartphone Generation' Deserve Statutory Online Education |website=HuffPost UK |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2017, she was made Shadow Policing Minister.<ref>{{cite web |last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/blog/louise-appointed-labours-shadow-policing-minister/ |title=Louise appointed Labour's Shadow Policing Minister |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=3 July 2017 |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref> Haigh has called for greater protection for police officers involved in vehicle pursuits, saying the current rules are \"hampering the ability of the police to apprehend very serious offenders\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/aug/04/police-stop-criminals-mopeds-skills-numbers |title=How can the police stop criminals on mopeds if they can't pursue them? |last=Haigh |first=Louise |date=4 August 2017 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=22 August 2017 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In this role she has raised the issue of stress and mental health of officers, citing a 77% rise in officer leave due to mental health between 2014 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/police-cuts_uk_5b48b647e4b0bc69a786a121|title=This Week Has Seen Policing Stretched To Its Limit \u2013 Time To Admit Cuts Have Cost Us Dear |date=13 July 2018 |work=HuffPost UK |accessdate=20 August 2018 }}</ref> She has called for a \"public health approach\" to reducing violent crime<ref>{{cite news |url=https://twitter.com/LouHaigh/status/1021847667645792256 |title=Louise Haigh MP on Twitter |work=Twitter |accessdate=20 August 2018 }}</ref> and blamed the rise in crime on government spending cuts to both police and other public services.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/news/2018/05/03/rising-crime-nationwide-and-in-south-yorkshire/ |title=Rising Crime Nationwide \u2013 And In South Yorkshire \u2013 Louise Haigh |website=Louise Haigh |accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaigh was declared the \"most hard-working\" new MP in February 2016 after a study of the activity of MPs elected in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-royston-smith-is-least-active-among-parliaments-new-members-a6886761.html |title=Tory MP Royston Smith is least active among Parliament's new members |first=Mark |last=Leftly |newspaper=The Independent| location=London |date=20 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-35629442 |title='Least active MP' Royston Smith defends record |publisher=BBC News|date=22 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/louise-haigh-most-hard-working-of-all-new-mps-1-7749890 |title=Louise Haigh most hard-working of all new MPs |first=Kate |last=Proctor |date=25 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016|newspaper=Yorkshire Post}}</ref>\n\nHaigh campaigned for the United Kingdom to remain a member of the European Union in the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/eu_referendum_pollling_day |title=Vote Remain today: Sheffield is better off in the EU \u2013 Louise Haigh, Labour Member of Parliament for Sheffield Heeley |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=23 June 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> In the 2016 Labour leadership election, Haigh supported [[Owen Smith]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/21/jeremy-corbyn-labour-owen-smith-leader|title=Jeremy Corbyn has served Labour well. But Owen Smith is the leader we need|date=21 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nHaigh was instrumental in revealing that hundreds of women had their [[Tax Credits Act 2002|tax credits]] stopped in error by US company [[Concentrix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneysavingexpert.com/news/protect/2016/09/hmrc-wont-extend-contract-for-tax-credit-checking-firm-concentrix|title=HMRC to axe tax credit checking firm Concentrix|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> The revelation led to an announcement that their [[HM Revenue and Customs|HMRC]] contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/concentrix-stripped-hmrc-contract-over-8827885|title=Concentrix to be stripped of HMRC contract over tax credits blunders|last=Byrne|first=Paul|date=13 September 2016|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> Panic alarms have been installed in Haigh's office and home by South Yorkshire Police after she received death threats for calling for a debate on the banning of [[Britain First]], the far-right group. [[South Yorkshire Police]] have provided her with uniformed and undercover protection as she attends to her constituency activities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pidd|first1=Helen|last2=Perraudin|first2=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/dec/15/female-mp-received-death-threats-for-calling-for-ban-on-britain-first|title=Female MP received death threats for calling for ban on Britain First|work=The Guardian|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 Haigh introduced a [[Private member's bill|Private Members\u2019 Bill]] calling for statutory leave from work for living organ donors, after a constituent complained of being given three days\u2019 unpaid holiday after donating bone marrow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2016-11-22/debates/BB1783C4-888B-4EFF-8B1F-ED8C0ED8C9C6/OrganDonors(Leave)|title=Organ Donors (Leave) \u2013 Hansard Online|website=hansard.parliament.uk|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Haigh introduced a [[Private member's bill|Private Members\u2019 Bill]] that would remove the automatic parental rights of fathers of children conceived through rape. The Bill would also establish an inquiry into the family court's handling of domestic abuse and violence against women and girls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/parentalrightsrapistsandfamilycourts.html|title=Parental Rights (Rapists) and Family Courts Bill 2017\u201319 \u2014 UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref> This Bill was borne out of Haigh's work with [[Sammy Woodhouse]], a survivor of child sexual exploitation, to increase protections for victims of abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/family-courts-must-protect-abuse-victims|title=Family Courts Must Protect Abuse Victims|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\nHaigh is a member of a number of [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Groups]], including the APPGs on Corporate Governance, Refugees, Colombia and Looked After Children. In July 2017 she was elected Vice Chair of the APPG on State Pension Inequality and in February 2019 became a Joint Chair of the APPG on Social Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/blog/vice-chair-of-state-pension-inequality-appg/|title=Vice Chair of State Pension Inequality APPG|website=www.louisehaigh.org.uk|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/launching-an-appg-on-social-care|title=Launching an APPG on Social Care|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nHaigh is concerned that forcing police to find more to pay for police pensions out of their general budget leaves less money for the police to protect the public.  Haigh stated, \"Forcing the police at the last minute to bear the huge cost of pension changes demonstrates the utter failure of ministers to grasp the crisis in policing caused by their cuts. They have played fast and loose with public safety and the police are right to step up and take action.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/oct/30/police-threaten-tories-with-legal-action-over-forces-budget-cuts|title=Police to sue government unless it backs down over cuts|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|date=30 October 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHaigh also feels it is wrong that the police are forced to deal with mental health crises that has been caused by underfunding of the NHS. Haigh said, \u201cThe government\u2019s underfunding of mental health services is a national scandal and passing the buck to our overstretched police officers is exacerbating the crisis in policing. It is frankly shocking that the police are often the only people who someone experiencing a mental health crisis can turn to. Nearly a decade of [[United Kingdom government austerity programme#Effects|brutal austerity]] has torn at the fabric of our society and the most vulnerable are being failed.\u201d<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/nhs-mental-health-police-crime-uk-failings-funding-government-a8653121.html NHS failings 'forcing police to respond to mental health incidents rather than crimes', report finds] ''[[The Independent]]''</ref>\n\nShe has spoken out about the crisis within the special education needs system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/opinion/columnists/a-tragedy-and-a-disgrace-the-state-of-special-educational-needs-funding-louise-haigh-1-9876630|title=A tragedy and a disgrace: the state of special educational needs funding \u2013 Louise Haigh|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref> She has said, \"School funding cuts that have resulted in the loss of teaching assistants, a narrower curriculum, and bigger class sizes have all made certain mainstream schools more hostile environments for children with SEN.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/supporting-children-with-sen|title=Supporting Children with SEN|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\nHaigh has also been outspoken in her opposition to fracking. She has said, \"I do not support fracking for a number of reasons: health and safety; the potential for earth tremors; the likely pollution of the water table; the impact on local communities in terms of disruption and subsidence; the fact that the chemicals used are deleterious to our health. Crucially, we also know that fracking contributes significantly to climate change and so, while all of the above means that fracking should absolutely not take place on an island as populated and as unconducive as ours, the evidence clearly shows that we should reject it outright.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/stop-fracking|title=Stop Fracking|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=louise-haigh/4473 |publicwhip=Louise_Haigh |theywork=louise_haigh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Meg Munn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Yorkshire and the Humber Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haigh, Louise Margaret}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sheffield High School, South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Politics of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Special Constabulary officers]]\n[[Category:Women Metropolitan Police officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Louise Haigh\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Louise Haigh MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| status = Interim\n| leader = [[Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start = 6 April 2020\n| term_end  = \n| predecessor = [[Tony Lloyd]] <small>(on medical leave}</small>\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Policing]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 3 July 2017\n| term_end1 = 6 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Lyn Brown (politician)|Lyn Brown]]\n| successor1 = [[Sarah Jones (politician)|Sarah Jones]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Digital Economy]]\n| leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 10 October 2016\n| term_end2 = 3 July 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Chi Onwurah]]\n| successor2 = [[Liam Byrne]]\n| office3 = [[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport|Shadow Minister for Civil Service and Digital Reform]]\n| leader3 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3 = 18 September 2015\n| term_end3 = 10 October 2016\n| predecessor3 = ''Office established''\n| successor3 = [[Steve Reed (politician)|Steve Reed]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]]\n| term_start4 = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4 = \n| predecessor4 = [[Meg Munn]]\n| successor4 = \n| majority4 = 8,520 (20.0%)\n| birth_name = Louise Margaret Haigh\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|7|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Sheffield]], [[South Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Nottingham]]\n| website = {{url|louisehaigh.org.uk|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Louise Margaret Haigh''' (born 22 July 1987) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician. She was elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]] at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], as the youngest Labour member of that parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000923 |title=Sheffield Heeley Parliamentary constituency |work=Election 2015 |publisher=BBC News |year=2015 |accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHaigh grew up on [[Abbeydale Road]], [[Sheffield]], and now lives in [[Norfolk Park]], Sheffield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/about_louise|title=About Louise|year=2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> She was educated at [[Sheffield High School, South Yorkshire|Sheffield High School]], an [[independent school]].<ref name=star-20140813>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/sheffield-heeley-candidate-could-be-youngest-mp-1-6781098 |title=Sheffield Heeley candidate could be youngest MP |first=Ellen |last=Beardmore |newspaper=The Star |location=Sheffield |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> She then studied Government and Economics at the [[London School of Economics]] but did not complete the course, and opted to study politics at the [[University of Nottingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sheffieldhighschool.org.uk/why-us/alumnae/the-alumnae-network/louise-haigh-mp/|title=Louise Haigh MP \u2013 Sheffield Girls School|website=Sheffield Girls High School}}</ref> Her grandfather and uncle were trade union officials.<ref name=\"Politics\">{{cite web |url=http://politics.co.uk/reference/louise-haigh |title=Louise Haigh |publisher= Politics.co.uk |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Haigh worked for the local council youth service between 2006 and 2008. She then began working in Parliament, where she was the co-ordinator of the All Party Parliamentary Group on International Corporate Responsibility.<ref name=\"Politics\"/> During this time, she was also a [[Unite the Union|Unite]] shop steward and volunteered as a [[Special Constable]] in the [[Metropolitan Special Constabulary]] between 2009 and 2011.<ref name=\"Profiles: Louise Haigh\">{{cite web|url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/20899/|title=Profiles: Louise Haigh|year=2015|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012, Haigh worked for [[Aviva]] as Public Policy Manager, responsible for corporate governance and responsible investment policy.<ref name=\"Profiles: Louise Haigh\"/><ref name=labour-cv>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/people/detail/louise-haigh |title=Louise Haigh |publisher=Labour Party |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asx.com.au/documents/public-consultations/aviva-plc-submission-15Nov13.pdf |title=Towards an agreement on corporate sustainability reporting |publisher=Aviva Investors |year=2013 |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHaigh was selected to stand for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]] in May 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/time-is-right-for-sheffield-mp-to-stand-down-1-6612067 |title='Time is right' for Sheffield MP to stand down |first=Ellen |last=Beardmore |newspaper=The Star| location=Sheffield |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> and was elected to Parliament at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|May 2015 general election]].\n\nHaigh was one of 36 Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Labour leadership election of 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election |work=The New Statesman |date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Haigh was appointed Shadow Minister for Civil Service and Digital Reform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/pages/labours-foi-review |title=Labour's FOI Review |publisher=Labour Party |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/jeremy-corbyn-appoints-mp-louise-haigh-labour-digital-brief |title=Jeremy Corbyn appoints MP Louise Haigh to Labour digital brief |first=Colin |last=Marrs |newspaper=Civil Service World |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> The role, newly expanded under Jeremy Corbyn,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukauthority.com/news/5629/louise-haigh-takes-labour-digital-role|title=Louise Haigh takes Labour digital role |first=Mark |last=Say |publisher=UK Authority.com |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> covers the Government's digital strategy, the [[Freedom of Information Act 2000|Freedom of Information Act]], data security and privacy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/sheffield-mp-louise-haigh-joins-shadow-cabinet-1-7469818 |title=Sheffield MP Louise Haigh joins Shadow Cabinet |first=Lauren |last=Clarke |newspaper=The Star |location=Sheffield |date=18 September 2015 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> In this role, Haigh was critical of a 2016 reshuffle of Permanent Secretaries which saw two fewer women as departmental heads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/interview/louise-haigh-interview-shadow-cabinet-office-minister-jeremy-corbyn-whitehall |title=Louise Haigh interview: the shadow Cabinet Office minister on Jeremy Corbyn, Whitehall diversity \u2013 and why the Tories have \"always understood\" civil service reform {{!}} Civil Service World |website=www.civilserviceworld.com |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> She opposed the closure of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills office in Sheffield city centre, saying the decision demonstrated \"contempt\" for the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civilserviceworld.com/articles/news/bis-sheffield-closure-confirmed-%E2%80%93-full-details-and-reaction-staff-unions-and-mps |title=BIS Sheffield closure confirmed \u2013 full details and reaction from staff, unions and MPs {{!}} Civil Service World |website=www.civilserviceworld.com |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2016, she was made Shadow Minister for the Digital Economy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/shadow_minister_digital_economy |title=Louise appointed Shadow Minister for the Digital Economy \u2013 Louise Haigh, Labour Member of Parliament for Sheffield Heeley |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> Haigh served in this role during the passage of the [[Digital Economy Act 2017|Digital Economy Act (2017)]] and introduced a number of amendments, including an obligation for television broadcasters to include subtitles and closed captioning in on-demand content online which was adopted by a subsequent Government amendment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cable.co.uk/news/digital-economy-bill-will-require-on-demand-programmes-to-include-subtitles-700001735/ |title=Digital Economy Bill will require on-demand programmes to include subtitles |website=www.cable.co.uk |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> She has repeatedly raised concerns about child protection online, including calling for social media companies to recognise \"that alongside their new-found power, they have responsibilities\" in dealing with harmful and illegal content.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/it-is-time-to-make-the-internet-giants-meet-their-responsibility-grfghjx6h |title=It is time to make the internet giants meet their responsibility |last=Haigh |first=Louise |accessdate=22 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\nShe also called for compulsory online education alongside sex and relationships education in schools, citing an 800% increase in children contacting the [[NSPCC]] about online abuse.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/louise-haigh-mp/sex-education_b_13126998.html?1479741341& |title=Why Our 'Smartphone Generation' Deserve Statutory Online Education |website=HuffPost UK |accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2017, she was made Shadow Policing Minister.<ref>{{cite web |last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/blog/louise-appointed-labours-shadow-policing-minister/ |title=Louise appointed Labour's Shadow Policing Minister |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=3 July 2017 |accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref> Haigh has called for greater protection for police officers involved in vehicle pursuits, saying the current rules are \"hampering the ability of the police to apprehend very serious offenders\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/aug/04/police-stop-criminals-mopeds-skills-numbers |title=How can the police stop criminals on mopeds if they can't pursue them? |last=Haigh |first=Louise |date=4 August 2017 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=22 August 2017 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In this role she has raised the issue of stress and mental health of officers, citing a 77% rise in officer leave due to mental health between 2014 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/police-cuts_uk_5b48b647e4b0bc69a786a121|title=This Week Has Seen Policing Stretched To Its Limit \u2013 Time To Admit Cuts Have Cost Us Dear |date=13 July 2018 |work=HuffPost UK |accessdate=20 August 2018 }}</ref> She has called for a \"public health approach\" to reducing violent crime<ref>{{cite news |url=https://twitter.com/LouHaigh/status/1021847667645792256 |title=Louise Haigh MP on Twitter |work=Twitter |accessdate=20 August 2018 }}</ref> and blamed the rise in crime on government spending cuts to both police and other public services.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/news/2018/05/03/rising-crime-nationwide-and-in-south-yorkshire/ |title=Rising Crime Nationwide \u2013 And In South Yorkshire \u2013 Louise Haigh |website=Louise Haigh |accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaigh was declared the \"most hard-working\" new MP in February 2016 after a study of the activity of MPs elected in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-royston-smith-is-least-active-among-parliaments-new-members-a6886761.html |title=Tory MP Royston Smith is least active among Parliament's new members |first=Mark |last=Leftly |newspaper=The Independent| location=London |date=20 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-35629442 |title='Least active MP' Royston Smith defends record |publisher=BBC News|date=22 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/louise-haigh-most-hard-working-of-all-new-mps-1-7749890 |title=Louise Haigh most hard-working of all new MPs |first=Kate |last=Proctor |date=25 February 2016 |accessdate=23 March 2016|newspaper=Yorkshire Post}}</ref>\n\nHaigh campaigned for the United Kingdom to remain a member of the European Union in the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum.<ref>{{cite web|last=Haigh |first=Louise |url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/eu_referendum_pollling_day |title=Vote Remain today: Sheffield is better off in the EU \u2013 Louise Haigh, Labour Member of Parliament for Sheffield Heeley |publisher=Louisehaigh.org.uk |date=23 June 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> In the 2016 Labour leadership election, Haigh supported [[Owen Smith]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/21/jeremy-corbyn-labour-owen-smith-leader|title=Jeremy Corbyn has served Labour well. But Owen Smith is the leader we need|date=21 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nHaigh was instrumental in revealing that hundreds of women had their [[Tax Credits Act 2002|tax credits]] stopped in error by US company [[Concentrix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moneysavingexpert.com/news/protect/2016/09/hmrc-wont-extend-contract-for-tax-credit-checking-firm-concentrix|title=HMRC to axe tax credit checking firm Concentrix|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> The revelation led to an announcement that their [[HM Revenue and Customs|HMRC]] contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/concentrix-stripped-hmrc-contract-over-8827885|title=Concentrix to be stripped of HMRC contract over tax credits blunders|last=Byrne|first=Paul|date=13 September 2016|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> Panic alarms have been installed in Haigh's office and home by South Yorkshire Police after she received death threats for calling for a debate on the banning of [[Britain First]], the far-right group. [[South Yorkshire Police]] have provided her with uniformed and undercover protection as she attends to her constituency activities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pidd|first1=Helen|last2=Perraudin|first2=Frances|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/dec/15/female-mp-received-death-threats-for-calling-for-ban-on-britain-first|title=Female MP received death threats for calling for ban on Britain First|work=The Guardian|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 Haigh introduced a [[Private member's bill|Private Members\u2019 Bill]] calling for statutory leave from work for living organ donors, after a constituent complained of being given three days\u2019 unpaid holiday after donating bone marrow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2016-11-22/debates/BB1783C4-888B-4EFF-8B1F-ED8C0ED8C9C6/OrganDonors(Leave)|title=Organ Donors (Leave) \u2013 Hansard Online|website=hansard.parliament.uk|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Haigh introduced a [[Private member's bill|Private Members\u2019 Bill]] that would remove the automatic parental rights of fathers of children conceived through rape. The Bill would also establish an inquiry into the family court's handling of domestic abuse and violence against women and girls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/parentalrightsrapistsandfamilycourts.html|title=Parental Rights (Rapists) and Family Courts Bill 2017\u201319 \u2014 UK Parliament|website=services.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref> This Bill was borne out of Haigh's work with [[Sammy Woodhouse]], a survivor of child sexual exploitation, to increase protections for victims of abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/family-courts-must-protect-abuse-victims|title=Family Courts Must Protect Abuse Victims|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\nHaigh is a member of a number of [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Groups]], including the APPGs on Corporate Governance, Refugees, Colombia and Looked After Children. In July 2017 she was elected Vice Chair of the APPG on State Pension Inequality and in February 2019 became a Joint Chair of the APPG on Social Care.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/blog/vice-chair-of-state-pension-inequality-appg/|title=Vice Chair of State Pension Inequality APPG|website=www.louisehaigh.org.uk|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/launching-an-appg-on-social-care|title=Launching an APPG on Social Care|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nHaigh is concerned that forcing police to find more to pay for police pensions out of their general budget leaves less money for the police to protect the public.  Haigh stated, \"Forcing the police at the last minute to bear the huge cost of pension changes demonstrates the utter failure of ministers to grasp the crisis in policing caused by their cuts. They have played fast and loose with public safety and the police are right to step up and take action.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/oct/30/police-threaten-tories-with-legal-action-over-forces-budget-cuts|title=Police to sue government unless it backs down over cuts|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|date=30 October 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHaigh also feels it is wrong that the police are forced to deal with mental health crises that has been caused by underfunding of the NHS. Haigh said, \u201cThe government\u2019s underfunding of mental health services is a national scandal and passing the buck to our overstretched police officers is exacerbating the crisis in policing. It is frankly shocking that the police are often the only people who someone experiencing a mental health crisis can turn to. Nearly a decade of [[United Kingdom government austerity programme#Effects|brutal austerity]] has torn at the fabric of our society and the most vulnerable are being failed.\u201d<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/nhs-mental-health-police-crime-uk-failings-funding-government-a8653121.html NHS failings 'forcing police to respond to mental health incidents rather than crimes', report finds] ''[[The Independent]]''</ref>\n\nShe has spoken out about the crisis within the special education needs system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/opinion/columnists/a-tragedy-and-a-disgrace-the-state-of-special-educational-needs-funding-louise-haigh-1-9876630|title=A tragedy and a disgrace: the state of special educational needs funding \u2013 Louise Haigh|website=www.yorkshirepost.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref> She has said, \"School funding cuts that have resulted in the loss of teaching assistants, a narrower curriculum, and bigger class sizes have all made certain mainstream schools more hostile environments for children with SEN.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/supporting-children-with-sen|title=Supporting Children with SEN|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\nHaigh has also been outspoken in her opposition to fracking. She has said, \"I do not support fracking for a number of reasons: health and safety; the potential for earth tremors; the likely pollution of the water table; the impact on local communities in terms of disruption and subsidence; the fact that the chemicals used are deleterious to our health. Crucially, we also know that fracking contributes significantly to climate change and so, while all of the above means that fracking should absolutely not take place on an island as populated and as unconducive as ours, the evidence clearly shows that we should reject it outright.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.louisehaigh.org.uk/stop-fracking|title=Stop Fracking|website=Louise Haigh|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=louise-haigh/4473 |publicwhip=Louise_Haigh |theywork=louise_haigh}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Meg Munn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Sheffield Heeley (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Heeley]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Yorkshire and the Humber Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haigh, Louise Margaret}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sheffield High School, South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Politics of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Special Constabulary officers]]\n[[Category:Women Metropolitan Police officers]]\n", "name_user": "Alex B4", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louise_Haigh"}
{"title_page": "Steel bridge competition", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=August 2013}}\n{{notability|Events|date=August 2013}}\n{{third-party|date=August 2013}}\n}}\nThe [[American Institute of Steel Construction]] '''steel bridge competition''' is a student contest that tests the knowledge and practicality of teams of university students in the field of [[structural engineering]]. Ideally, the design and fabrication of the bridge is conceived and completed entirely by the students and the participation of the students in the process is highly encouraged. Some schools may not have the proper facilities and guidance necessary to erect the model bridge and may work with a commercial fabricator. However, the students must be fully responsible for the design and instructions, they must coordinate with the fabricator, and they must monitor the construction process.\n\nThe bridges must follow specifications explained in the rule book. The rules of the competition are changed annually to further enhance the quality of the competition and to prevent the submission of an already existing bridge.\n\nThe competition gets additional sponsorship from the [[American Iron and Steel Institute]], the National Steel Bridge Alliance, [[Nucor Corporation]], and The James F. Lincoln Arc Welding Foundation.<ref>[http://www.aisc.org/Content/NavigationMenu/Learning_Opportunities/University_Programs/Student_Competitions1/AISC_Student_Steel_Bridge_Competition/AISC_Student_Steel_Bridge_Competition.htm AISC | AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe steel bridge competition, in its embryonic form, began as a miniature bridge design competition using balsa wood to see which competitor's bridge is the best. [http://steelstructures.com/sstc-consulting-services/robert-e-shaw-jr-pe/ Robert E. Shaw Jr.], Associate Director of Education for the American Institute of Steel Construction, initiated the steel bridge competition in the spring of 1987 and was honored by the AISC in 2000 for his achievement. The first teams to compete were [[Lawrence Technological University]](who hosted the competition), [[Wayne State University]], and [[Michigan Technological University]].<ref>Shaw, Robert \"Bridging the Gap: From Classroom Learning to Hands-On Experience\". http://steelstructures.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Bridging-the-Gap-Classroom-Learning-to-Hands-On-Experience.pdf</ref> In 1988, the competition grew to four regional conference competitions: North Central at the [[University of Detroit]], Great Lakes at [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]], Carolinas at the [[University of North Carolina - Charlotte]], and Ohio Valley at the [[University of Louisville]]. In 1989, nine conferences held steel bridge-building competitions: Upstate New York, Carolinas, Ohio Valley, North Central, Midwest, Mid-Continent, Rocky Mountain, Southeast, and Texas. [[Michigan State University]] dominated their Conference with bridges built quickly with innovative, lightweight designs that set the pattern for future competitions.  In 1992, Fromy Rosenberg, who was the new Director of AISC College Relations, began the first ever National Student Steel Bridge Competition.<ref>Hatfield, Frank. \"History of the Competition\". http://nssbc.info/ 2007</ref>\n\n==Past champions==\nThe following are past champions.<ref>\"Past NSSBC Champs\", http://nssbc.info/</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Host\n! Champion\n|-\n| 1992\n| [[Michigan State University]]\n| [[Michigan State University]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| [[Southern Polytechnic State University]]\n| [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| [[San Diego State University]]\n| [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[University of Florida]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|SUNY Buffalo]]\n| [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]]\n| [[University of Florida]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| [[Colorado State University]]\n| [[University of Southwestern Louisiana]]\n|-\n| 1999\n| [[University of Alaska Anchorage]]\n| [[University of Nevada, Reno]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| [[Texas A&M University]]\n| [[California State University, Chico]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| [[Clemson University]]\n| [[Clemson University]]\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[University of Wisconsin, Madison]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[San Diego State University]]\n| [[University of Michigan]]\n|-\n| 2004\n| [[Colorado School of Mines]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[University of Central Florida]]\n| [[University of California, Davis]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[University of Utah]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[California State University, Northridge]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[University of Florida]]\n| [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[University of Nevada Las Vegas]]\n|[[SUNY Canton]]\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Purdue University]]\n|[[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Texas A&M University]]\n|[[Lakehead University]]\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Clemson University]]\n|[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2013\n|[[University of Washington]]\n|[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2014\n|[[University of Akron]]\n|[[University of California, Davis]]\n|-\n|2015\n|[[University of Missouri, Kansas City]]\n|[[University of Florida]]\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Brigham Young University]]\n|[[\u00c9cole de Technologie Sup\u00e9rieure]]\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Oregon State University]]\n|[[\u00c9cole de Technologie Sup\u00e9rieure]]\n|-\n|2018\n|[[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]\n|[[Lafayette College]]\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Southern Illinois University Carbondale]]\n|[[Lafayette College]]\n|}\n\n==Scoring==\nFor a full description of the 2016 rules and regulations, including the scoring go to: <ref>2011 Steel Bridge Rules, Section 7. http://www.aisc.org/WorkArea/showcontent.aspx?id=21576</ref>\n\nThe different categories in the competition that will be judged are:\n\n#Display - Includes appearance of bridge, identification of the school on the bridge, and the poster that explains the thought process and includes sponsors, advisors, and technicians. (Display is only used as a tie breaker, however, the lack of information either on the poster or on the bridge itself will results in an added weight penalty to the bridge)\n#Construction Speed - The team that constructs the bridge with the quickest time (including added time penalties) wins this category\n#Construction economy - A formula is devised to calculate a dollar amount based on the number of builders, the time of the assembly, and the use of temporary piers. The team with the lowest dollar amount wins this category\n#Lightness - The team with the lightest bridge (including weight penalties) wins this category.\n#Stiffness - The team with the lowest aggregate deflection wins this category.\n#Structural efficiency - A formula is devised to calculate a dollar amount based on the weight and deflection of the bridge. The team with the lowest dollar amount wins this category\n\nThe overall winner has the lowest sum from the construction economy and structural efficiency categories.\n\n==Regional advancement==\nGetting to the National Competition - Teams compete at regional conferences around the United States. The top teams from each region are invited to compete at the National Competition each year.\n\n*In a region of 1-4 teams, the top competitor advances to nationals\n*In a region of 5-10 teams, the top two competitor advances to nationals\n*In a region with 11 or more teams, the top three competitors advances to nationals.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\nAISC Student Steel Bridge Competition Information: [https://www.aisc.org/education/university-programs/student-steel-bridge-competition/ aisc.org/studentsteelbridgecompetition]\n\n[[Category:Awards established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Structural engineering awards]]\n[[Category:Student events]]\n[[Category:Awards of the American Society of Civil Engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=August 2013}}\n{{notability|Events|date=August 2013}}\n{{third-party|date=August 2013}}\n}}\nThe [[American Institute of Steel Construction]] '''steel bridge competition''' is a student contest that tests the knowledge and practicality of teams of university students in the field of [[structural engineering]]. Ideally, the design and fabrication of the bridge is conceived and completed entirely by the students and the participation of the students in the process is highly encouraged. Some schools may not have the proper facilities and guidance necessary to erect the model bridge and may work with a commercial fabricator. However, the students must be fully responsible for the design and instructions, they must coordinate with the fabricator, and they must monitor the construction process.\n\nThe bridges must follow specifications explained in the rule book. The rules of the competition are changed annually to further enhance the quality of the competition and to prevent the submission of an already existing bridge.\n\nThe competition gets additional sponsorship froom the [[American Iron and Steel Institute]], the National Steel Bridge Alliance, [[Nucor Corporation]], and The James F. Lincoln Arc Welding Foundation.<ref>[http://www.aisc.org/Content/NavigationMenu/Learning_Opportunities/University_Programs/Student_Competitions1/AISC_Student_Steel_Bridge_Competition/AISC_Student_Steel_Bridge_Competition.htm AISC | AISC Student Steel Bridge Competition<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe steel bridge competition, in its embryonic form, began as a miniature bridge design competition using balsa wood to see which competitor's bridge is the best. [http://steelstructures.com/sstc-consulting-services/robert-e-shaw-jr-pe/ Robert E. Shaw Jr.], Associate Director of Education for the American Institute of Steel Construction, initiated the steel bridge competition in the spring of 1987 and was honored by the AISC in 2000 for his achievement. The first teams to compete were [[Lawrence Technological University]](who hosted the competition), [[Wayne State University]], and [[Michigan Technological University]].<ref>Shaw, Robert \"Bridging the Gap: From Classroom Learning to Hands-On Experience\". http://steelstructures.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Bridging-the-Gap-Classroom-Learning-to-Hands-On-Experience.pdf</ref> In 1988, the competition grew to four regional conference competitions: North Central at the [[University of Detroit]], Great Lakes at [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]], Carolinas at the [[University of North Carolina - Charlotte]], and Ohio Valley at the [[University of Louisville]]. In 1989, nine conferences held steel bridge-building competitions: Upstate New York, Carolinas, Ohio Valley, North Central, Midwest, Mid-Continent, Rocky Mountain, Southeast, and Texas. [[Michigan State University]] dominated their Conference with bridges built quickly with innovative, lightweight designs that set the pattern for future competitions.  In 1992, Fromy Rosenberg, who was the new Director of AISC College Relations, began the first ever National Student Steel Bridge Competition.<ref>Hatfield, Frank. \"History of the Competition\". http://nssbc.info/ 2007</ref>\n\n==Past champions==\nThe following are past champions.<ref>\"Past NSSBC Champs\", http://nssbc.info/</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Host\n! Champion\n|-\n| 1992\n| [[Michigan State University]]\n| [[Michigan State University]]\n|-\n| 1993\n| [[Southern Polytechnic State University]]\n| [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| [[San Diego State University]]\n| [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[University of Florida]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|SUNY Buffalo]]\n| [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| [[California State Polytechnic University, Pomona]]\n| [[University of Florida]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| [[Colorado State University]]\n| [[University of Southwestern Louisiana]]\n|-\n| 1999\n| [[University of Alaska Anchorage]]\n| [[University of Nevada, Reno]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| [[Texas A&M University]]\n| [[California State University, Chico]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| [[Clemson University]]\n| [[Clemson University]]\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[University of Wisconsin, Madison]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[San Diego State University]]\n| [[University of Michigan]]\n|-\n| 2004\n| [[Colorado School of Mines]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[University of Central Florida]]\n| [[University of California, Davis]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| [[University of Utah]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[California State University, Northridge]]\n| [[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[University of Florida]]\n| [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2009\n|[[University of Nevada Las Vegas]]\n|[[SUNY Canton]]\n|-\n|2010\n|[[Purdue University]]\n|[[North Dakota State University]]\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Texas A&M University]]\n|[[Lakehead University]]\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Clemson University]]\n|[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2013\n|[[University of Washington]]\n|[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n|-\n|2014\n|[[University of Akron]]\n|[[University of California, Davis]]\n|-\n|2015\n|[[University of Missouri, Kansas City]]\n|[[University of Florida]]\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Brigham Young University]]\n|[[\u00c9cole de Technologie Sup\u00e9rieure]]\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Oregon State University]]\n|[[\u00c9cole de Technologie Sup\u00e9rieure]]\n|-\n|2018\n|[[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]]\n|[[Lafayette College]]\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Southern Illinois University Carbondale]]\n|[[Lafayette College]]\n|}\n\n==Scoring==\nFor a full description of the 2016 rules and regulations, including the scoring go to: <ref>2011 Steel Bridge Rules, Section 7. http://www.aisc.org/WorkArea/showcontent.aspx?id=21576</ref>\n\nThe different categories in the competition that will be judged are:\n\n#Display - Includes appearance of bridge, identification of the school on the bridge, and the poster that explains the thought process and includes sponsors, advisors, and technicians. (Display is only used as a tie breaker, however, the lack of information either on the poster or on the bridge itself will results in an added weight penalty to the bridge)\n#Construction Speed - The team that constructs the bridge with the quickest time (including added time penalties) wins this category\n#Construction economy - A formula is devised to calculate a dollar amount based on the number of builders, the time of the assembly, and the use of temporary piers. The team with the lowest dollar amount wins this category\n#Lightness - The team with the lightest bridge (including weight penalties) wins this category.\n#Stiffness - The team with the lowest aggregate deflection wins this category.\n#Structural efficiency - A formula is devised to calculate a dollar amount based on the weight and deflection of the bridge. The team with the lowest dollar amount wins this category\n\nThe overall winner has the lowest sum from the construction economy and structural efficiency categories.\n\n==Regional advancement==\nGetting to the National Competition - Teams compete at regional conferences around the United States. The top teams from each region are invited to compete at the National Competition each year.\n\n*In a region of 1-4 teams, the top competitor advances to nationals\n*In a region of 5-10 teams, the top two competitor advances to nationals\n*In a region with 11 or more teams, the top three competitors advances to nationals.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\nAISC Student Steel Bridge Competition Information: [https://www.aisc.org/education/university-programs/student-steel-bridge-competition/ aisc.org/studentsteelbridgecompetition]\n\n[[Category:Awards established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Structural engineering awards]]\n[[Category:Student events]]\n[[Category:Awards of the American Society of Civil Engineers]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "LEAPIN' LIZARDS!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steel_bridge_competition"}
